<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Targets, Dates to Be Set for EU Development Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 28 (Xinhua) -- European Commission chief
Romano Prodi on Monday proposed to the European Union (EU) that
targets and dates be set for the 15-nation bloc's development
program.
</P>
<P>
In an agenda sent to the EU's rotating presidency Portugal,
European Commission President Romano Prodi said that the EU should
make most of the current favorable economic conditions to proceed
with the economic reform so as to prepare the union for a
knowledge-based economy and society.
</P>
<P>
The commission is the executive body of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said that the coming EU summit in Lisbon would be the
opportunity for establishing targets and dates besides identifying
priorities and setting long-term goals.
</P>
<P>
The commission president pinned down on six priorities to be
focused by the entire union. They included the implementation of
an information society via electronic networking, the further
improvement of the internal market by 2004 and the full
integration of the financial markets by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said, "The measures proposed are ambitious but achievable.
If the commission, the EU member states and European citizens at
all levels summon the political energy and courage to implement
this ambitious integrated program, Europe will see a new
renaissance with full employment and prosperity."
</P>
<P>
The EU has, through the last decade, formed an internal market,
an economic and monetary union, by the launch of the single
currency for 11 member states.
</P>
<P>
The commission has projected the economic growth at 3 percent
for this year and next and a net job creation of above 1 percent,
that converts to 1.5 million new jobs each year.
</P>
<P>
Other favorable economic conditions included low inflation and
reduced public sector deficits while the stock of government debt
as a percentage of gross domestic product has been on a downward
path, commission sources said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's agenda also included as a second strategy investment in
the European citizens. This strategy includes increased investment
in education, training for the knowledge-based economy and the
promotion of life-long learning.
</P>
<P>
One tangible target set for this strategy is all EU schools
will be connected to the Internet in the year 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
