<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladeshi Opposition Demands Scrapping of PSA By Pan Xiaozhu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's opposition launched
a countrywide dawn-to-dusk general strike Monday, demanding the
scrapping of the controversial Public Security Act (PSA).
</P>
<P>
The strike ended in the evening peacefully barring few stray
incidents of violence which left at least 15 people injured.
Police arrested six people on charges of violence during the
strike.
</P>
<P>
Life in the capital was almost normal during the general strike.
Leaders and workers of the ruling Awami League and its front
organizations marched through city streets protesting the strike
called by the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP)-led opposition
alliance.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party urged people to become more active against the
anti-development activities.
</P>
<P>
Monday's strike, the third of its kind this month, was prompted
by the passage of the tough PSA in the government's bid to come to
grips with serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance launched a two-day general strike on
February 2-3 and a staggering three-day shutdown from February 15
to 17 demanding the scrapping of the law which they said was
enacted to suppress the opposition's oust-government movement.
</P>
<P>
President Shahabuddin Ahmed on February 14 gave his assent to
the controversial PSA passed in parliament on January 30. The bill
seeks summary trials for crimes like damaging property and
vehicles, obstructing traffic, mugging and extortion. It proposes
to make those offenses non-bailable.
</P>
<P>
After the PSA was adopted, leaders of the BNP-led opposition
and the 11-party left-democratic alliance met the president and
asked him not to assent to the PSA, arguing that the PSA was
adopted in parliament as a "Money Bill," violating the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
As the opposition is intensifying its oust-government movement,
the controversy on the PSA between the president and the prime
minister in the past few days again made the political situation
in the country more complicated.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question during the "face-to-face with the
countrymen" program on TV last Friday, Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina noted that the president signed the draft of the PSA before
it was presented to parliament as a "Money Bill."
</P>
<P>
The President House last Saturday took the unusual step of
issuing a public statement to dispel "the impression being created
" in the country. "This idea is completely wrong," said a press
release issued by the President Press Secretary from the President
House.
</P>
<P>
"It has been clearly stated in the prime minister's proposal
that it involves expenses from the public exchequer. But the
question of involvement of public money does not necessarily mean
Money Bill," the press release stressed, adding that the speaker
is to decide if it is a "Money Bill" or not after the passage of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
Leading jurists of the country Sunday said the debate between
the president and the prime minister was undesirable after the
bill had been signed.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that politically, the PSA melodrama
signaled the end of a possible role of the president as a
moderator in the power struggle between the ruling party and the
opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
