<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke022870 --Vietnam, Turkey to Boost Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnam and Turkey Inter-
Governmental Committee held its first meeting here on Monday to
discuss measures to boost bilateral trade, Vietnam News Agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Turkish Minister of State M. Ali Irtemcelic
noted that despite a considerable growth, trade turnover between
Vietnam and Turkey over recent years has yet to meet the potential
of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ali Irtemcelic stressed that the two countries should work out
concrete measures to diversify the forms of trade and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed measures to encourage the business circles to
further participate in trade fairs in their respective countries
and accelerate other trade promotion activities so as to open up
opportunities for business executives and investors of the two
countries to better understand each other's markets and win more
contracts.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Minister of Trade Vu Khoan reaffirmed that the
Vietnamese government will continue to make efforts to promote
cooperation among the business circles of the two countries in the
years to come.
</P>
<P>
Khoan also set Vietnam's goal of expanding cooperation with
Turkey in new areas such as banking, aviation, agriculture and
construction.
</P>
<P>
Trade turnover between Vietnam and Turkey in the first 11
months of last year reached 15.9 million U.S. dollars with Vietnam
enjoying a surplus of 7.7 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turkey exports to Vietnam mainly electricity transformers,
copper wire, conductive materials and steel products, while
importing footwear, latex and crude oil from Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
