<HEADLINE> Sharif's Entire Defense Team Boycotts Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The entire defense team for
Pakistan's former prime minister Nawaz Sharif and the co-accused
Monday boycotted the case to protest the court's restriction on
Sharif's testifying in public.
</P>
<P>
"We are boycotting this hearing because we have been denied the
right of defense...we are walking out in protest," Iqbal Raad, a
member of the defense team said.
</P>
<P>
He said that no defense lawyer would be in the Anti-Terrorism
Court when it resumes proceedings on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Special Public Prosecutor in the plane hijacking
case, Barrister Zahoorul Haq, expressed astonishment over the
boycott by the lawyers, saying the judge of the Anti-Terrorism
Court on February 25 accepted his application and decided that the
statements of Sharif and the other accused in the case should be
of two parts.
</P>
<P>
In the second part, the accused may give oral or written
statements as required by the law. If they give written statements
then they can be examined by the court and if the accused give
oral statements, whatever they will say will be recorded and then
the court will decide at the appropriate stage as to whether the
same or part of the statements should not be released to the
public or media for public consumption.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that Nawaz Sharif's statement could not be allowed
appearance in the press because he (Sharif) may touch upon state
secret in his statement or may cast aspersions on the conduct of
the judge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
