<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Tamil rebels release Four Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) Monday released four Sri Lankan military personnel
they had been holding for more than six years, official television
reported.
</P>
<P>
Three Sri Lankan army soldiers and a naval cadet were handed
over to the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) at
Mallavi in the north of the island country Monday afternoon, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The handover ceremony took place at the political office of the
LTTE at Mallavi.
</P>
<P>
The six military persons were to be taken to the government-
held town of Vavuniya for debriefing and medical checks, according
to ICRC sources here.
</P>
<P>
No explanation has been given by the LTTE for the releases,
which came at the end of a visit to the men by their relatives
arranged through the ICRC, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been waging a 17-year-old war against the
government for a separate Tamil state in the north and east of Sri
Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
