<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Recount Votes in Tehran to Ascertain Accuracy of Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Ballots from 500 boxes of
Tehran constituency are to be recounted and double-checked to
ascertain accuracy of the 6th Majlis (Parliament) polling results,
an Interior Ministry official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In light of the feelings of the Central Council for Polls Watch,
and of the recommendations of the Executive Council, ballots from
500 boxes of a total of 3,111 would be recounted Tuesday night,
said Seyed-Javad Qadimi Zaker, director general of national polling
at the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The recounting of the votes will be in the presence of observers
from the Council of Guardians and the Interior Ministry and will
take five days or probably less, the official was quoted by the
Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added that results would be released for public information
as soon as the recounting ended.
</P>
<P>
The official expressed hope that the recounting of ballots from
those boxes would "dispel any anxiety about the likelihood of
faulty counting of ballots, in the first counting, at Tehran
constituency."
</P>
<P>
The final election results of Tehran constituency was announced
last Saturday after a two-day delay, during which votes from 105
boxes were recounted by related bodies to "remove all doubt."
</P>
<P>
According to the results, reformers supporting President
Mohammed Khatami won most of the 30 seats, while former president
Hashemi Rafsanjani got only 25.58 percent of the votes, ranking
30th in the list.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, currently heading the powerful State Expediency
Council, posed as a centrist in the elections, but he is widely
believed to an ally of the conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Newspaper reports said Ali Akbar Rahmani, who ranked 31st in the
Tehran constituency, doubted the accuracy of the vote counting,
claiming that his seat might have been unjustly taken by
Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
The 6th Majlis polling, held on February 18, was rather
sensitive, because it was another major fighting between reformers
and the conservatives since the 1997 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Latest polling results showed that 225 of a total of 290 seats
in the expanded new Majlis have been confirmed, with reformists
pocketing 170, the conservatives 45, and independents 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
