<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Breakthrough on Resumption of Syrian-Israeli Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"There is no truth to these rumors, reports, suggestions that
there is an imminent announcement of a breakthrough n the Syria
track. I wish that were true. It's not true," State Department
spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He was answering questions that some Arab diplomats in Amman
had suggested Syria and Israel would resume peace talks in late
March.
</P>
<P>
"We are working with the Syrians and the Israelis on a number
of levels to try to make that possible, but there is no imminent
announcement that I am aware of," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Monday that there was still an "enormous
amount" of work to be done before the two sides can agree to
resume the talks, which suspended in January because of no
agreement was reached on the Israeli withdrawal from the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh told reporters in
Washington that his government would not agree to the other side's
terms on the Golan Heights before negotiations starts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says Still Hopeful on Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 29 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
Tuesday that he remains committed and hopeful about the Middle
East peace process despite his envoy's failure to bring Israel and
the Palestinians back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
"I am not throwing in the towel," Clinton told reporters before
leaving the White House for a political trip to Florida.
</P>
<P>
U.S. envoy Dennis Ross was back to Washington after a week of
unsuccessful efforts to restart talks on implementing an interim
accord and negotiating a peace treaty between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said it would be a great mistake to overread the
significance of Ross's coming home. "He's coming home because we
need to talk about where we are now and where we're going, but
there's no throwing in the towel here," he added. 
</P>
