<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Exports Weaken As Domestic Demand Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Household spending in Britain
is rising at its fastest annual rate since the late 1980s, fueling
fears that the pace of domestic demand growth has become
unsustainable.
</P>
<P>
Despite the negative effects inflicted upon growth by the
recent drop in exports, the UK's economy as a whole grew by 2
percent in 1999, which was more than initial estimates.
</P>
<P>
David Clementi, deputy governor of the Bank of England, told a
business gathering that there could now be "an opportunity to wait
and see how the economy develops," indicating the possibility of
an interest rate standstill.
</P>
<P>
Sharp rises in spending in the shops and on financial services
helped household expenditure to rise 0.8 percent in the last three
months of 1999, according to new official data.
</P>
<P>
Some economists said the weakness of exports seemed a little
peculiar, given they had contributed positively to growth in the
previous two quarters.
</P>
<P>
"I an a little wary of these figures," said Danny Gabay, UK
economist at J.P. Morgan. "Net trade seems surprisingly weak, and
stockbuilding surprisingly strong. I would expect to see some
revisions to the composition of demand. " 
</P>
</TEXT>
