<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Reiterates Security Council Sets Policy on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday reiterated that it is up to the United Nations
Security Council to set the policies on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Annan said it was not Von Sponeck, the
departing U.N. humanitarian coordinator in Iraq who will quit the
job on March 31, or anybody in the U.N. Secretariat to set the
policies.
</P>
<P>
Annan said Sponeck, who has served the United Nations for 32
years, did gave him indications to some of the difficulties with
the U.N. oil-for-food program in Iraq and the appropriate ways to
improve it.
</P>
<P>
U.N. civil servants had to implement U.N. policies, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of U.N. resolutions on Iraq had not been
easy for anyone and it was not going to be any different for Hans
Blix, executive chairman of the United Nations Monitoring,
Verification and Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC) who will take
office Wednesday, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
He was very experienced, a good diplomat, a good leader and a
good manager, and he would be able to work with the Iraqi
authorities to make progress, the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
Sponeck met the U.N. chief Monday and briefed him on the
implementation of the U.N. oil-for-food program in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sponeck, whose resignation is widely seen here to protest the U.
N. sanctions against Iraq, has on occasions criticized the U.N.
policy, saying it has resulted in "a true human tragedy and the
oil-for-food program was not even meeting the minimum requirements
of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that the sanctions against and the arms inspections
in Iraq be separated.
</P>
<P>
He will brief the 15-member Security Council on the program
Tuesday afternoon. Some of the members have expressed their deep
concern over the failure of the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
