<HEADLINE> OAPEC Forecasts Higher World Oil Demand This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Arab
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) has predicted that the world
oil demand will rise throughout this year compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
The world will need some 78 million barrels of oil per day in
the first quarter of 2000, up 1.5 million barrels from the first
three months of 1999, OAPEC said in its monthly newsletter
available here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The global demand for oil is likely to drop by 2.9 million bpd
in the second quarter to reach 75.1 million bpd. But the amount is
still 2.1 million barrels higher than that of the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
The third quarter will witness an increase of some 700,000
barrels in the world oil demand with the total amount expected to
rise to 75.7 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Oil demand in the last quarter of 2000 will reach around 78.9
million bpd, up by 1.6 million bpd compared to the corresponding
period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
With regard to oil supply, the Kuwait-based OAPEC said that the
supplies and demands are likely to be kept in balance, hinting that
oil producing countries will pump more oil into the international
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
