<HEADLINE> Iraq to Attend Tripartite Committee Meetings on MIAs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) Speaker Saadoun Hamadi said Iraq is ready to attend
the Tripartite Committee meetings handling the missings in action
(MIAs) in the Gulf War, the Iraqi News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the European Parliament, Hamadi said that Iraq
will be present at the meetings of the Committee, which comprises
Iraq, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, but under the auspices of the
International Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
The Committee was formed after the 1991 Gulf War to handle the
issue of prisoners of war (POW) and MIAs, under the supervision of
the U.S., Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
Iraq quit the Committee after the U.S. and Britain launched air
strikes in December 1998 to retaliate what they called Iraq's
failure to fully cooperate with the U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament adopted a resolution last month, calling
on the Iraqi government to abide by the relevant U.N. resolutions,
and free all Kuwaiti POWs it still keeps.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the resolution, Hamadi expressed deep sorrow and
pointed out that the European Parliament failed to take into
consideration of Iraq's viewpoints regarding such an important
issue relating to two rival parties.
</P>
<P>
Hamadi said that Iraq has repatriated all Kuwaiti POWs in
accordance with Geneva treaties, and has exerted continuous efforts
to probe into the fate of the MIAs.
</P>
<P>
However, Kuwait has alleged that Iraq still holds more than 600
Kuwaiti POWs. Iraq, on the other hand, claims that the Kuwaiti
authority fails to account for the whereabouts of some 1,100 Iraqi
MIAs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
