<HEADLINE> Russia, Turkey Common in Fighting Separatism: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Russian Deputy Prime Minister
Ilya Klebanov, who started an official visit to Turkey on Tuesday,
said that Ankara and Moscow share same ideas and have mutual
understanding against separatism in each country.
</P>
<P>
Klebanov said Russia has never supported Turkey's rebel group,
the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which has been fighting since
1984 for an independent Kurdish state in the southeast of Turkey,
the Anatolia News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He praised Turkey's support for Russian struggle against Chechen
terrorists in the Northern Caucasus, saying that "Russia's
initiatives to destroy the international terrorism in Chechnya is
in the benefit of both Russia and Turkey."
</P>
<P>
Russia has made sweep victory in fighting Chechnya separatism.
Klebanov said that Russia is launching a crackdown against Islamic
fundamentalism in Northern Caucasus as Turkey did.
</P>
<P>
Klebanov brought Turkish President Suleyman Demirel the response
letter from acting Russian President Vladimir Putin, on Turkey's
proposal to maintain stability in the Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey is the prior and most important partner of
Russia, so both countries should coordinate positions on regional
and international issues.
</P>
<P>
He will meet with Demirel and Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit to discuss issues ranging from economic cooperation to
regional policies including the Caucasus and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Russian firms have been struggling to secure Turkey's lucrative
attack helicopter and tank tenders which big western firms are
competing for. Bargaining between energy-shortage Turkey and Russia
has also continued over buying electricity from Russia via Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey meets its gas demands by buying natural gas from Russia.
In addition to the existing pipeline through the Balkans, Russia is
constructing another pipeline, the Blue Stream project, under the
Black Sea to supply gas to Turkey. 
</P>
