<HEADLINE> Egypt Has Full Confidence in Barak: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak has full confidence in Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
intention on peace, an Egyptian envoy said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Osama el-Baz, Mubarak's political adviser, stressed during his
meeting with Barak that Mubarak believed Barak is determined to
move forward the peace process with the Arabs, a statement released
by Barak's office said.
</P>
<P>
Barak briefed el-Baz on the current deadlocks in the peace
process with Syria and the Palestinians, and promised to seize all
chances to advance on both peace tracks.
</P>
<P>
The senior adviser's 20-hour visit was regarded by most analysts
here as an effort to improve the Egyptian-Israeli ties and those of
their leaders, which suffered a confidence crisis in the past few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was fueled by Israel's air raids on Lebanon's
infrastructure targets in retaliation for Lebanese Hezbollah
guerrillas' attacks in the Israeli-occupied security zone in south
Lebanon, which had killed seven Israeli soldiers and wounded a
dozen since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
After the air strikes and Israel's further threat to attack
civilian targets in Lebanon, Mubarak made a surprise visit to
Lebanon earlier this month, the first by an Egyptian head of state
since 1952, to demonstrate Egypt's support for Lebanon and justify
its resistance against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Mubarak reportedly told Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat during one of their meetings that Barak had repeated his
commitment in a recent telephone call to move forward the peace
talks with the Palestinians, but the Egyptian leader didn't believe
he was serious.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's remarks were noticeable as Egypt, the first Arab
country in the region to sign a peace treaty with Israel in 1979,
usually is careful with criticizing Barak in public. Egypt had
indeed used its political leverage on Arafat to prevent crises.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Egypt's stepped-up criticism was meant to
send Barak a signal that Cairo is increasingly disappointed at the
pace of the peace talks and Mubarak fears that a freeze in the
process could create regional instability.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks, resumed last December after a
45-month break, hit a snag again in January after two rounds over
Israeli troops withdrawal from the Golan Heights, captured from
Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian track, all talks, interim and the final-
status, were suspended indefinitely after a summit meeting earlier
this month between Barak and Arafat failed to resolve their
difference over Israeli troops withdrawal map of 6.1 percent West
Bank land.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also missed a February 13 deadline for a framework
agreement on final peace as stipulated by the Sharm el Sheikh
memorandum signed last September.
</P>
<P>
To mend fences with Egypt, Barak had sent his top aide Danny
Yatom and Foreign Minister David Levy's adviser Alon Pinkas to
Cairo to explain Israel's policy on peace and clear the air between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Although Israel and Egypt made peace more than two decades ago,
Israel always complains that no mutually warm relationship has
evolved between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
