<HEADLINE> Annan Hopes Iraq To Show Flexibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday expressed the hope that Iraq would show
flexibility in dealing with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Annan was responding to the remarks by Nizar Hamdoon, Iraq's
ambassador to the United Nations, who said Tuesday that Iraq still
rejects a U.N. resolution adopted last December.
</P>
<P>
"I think that other governments are also in touch with the
Iraqi authorities. I think we are still at the early stages of
this vote," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Blix will start formally on the 1st of March and begin to
work out his plans. I am sure at an appropriate time he will be in
touch with the Iraqi authorities," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that their position will be flexible," Annan added.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council adopted a resolution last
December which created the United Nations Monitoring, Verification
and Inspection Commission (UNMOVIC) to replace the now defunct
United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM has been barred by Iraq from returning to the
country to resume the weapons inspection. The UNSCOM withdrew from
Iraq days before the U.S.-led military strikes against Iraq in
December 1998.
</P>
<P>
Hans Blix, executive chairman of the UNMOVIC, will take office
on March 1. Under a U.N. resolution of last December, he will have
45 days after taking office to make up the UNMOVIC and to draw the
UNMOVIC's work plan.
</P>
<P>
So far, Iraq has refused to accept the resolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
