<HEADLINE> Jospin Reaffirms His Condemnation of Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin Tuesday reaffirmed his condemnation of the Lebanese Shiite
guerrilla force Hezbollah, accusing it of deliberately using
violence to block the peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
In a debate at the French National Assembly, Jospin indirectly
accused President Jacques Chirac of adopting a policy of
impeachment toward those who use force and said that such a policy
would make France appear weak in front of "violence and fanaticism.
"
</P>
<P>
Jospin said last Thursday during a visit in Israel that France
condemns the attacks by Hezbollah and all other terrorist attacks
upon Israeli troops and civilians.
</P>
<P>
His remarks triggered fury among Arab countries and resulted in
a violent attack upon himself by stone-throwing Palestinians when
he visited the University of Bir Zeit in the West Bank Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The statement was also sharply criticized by Chirac and France'
s rightwing opposition as harmful to France's traditional
relations with Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
In Tuesday's parliament debate, Jospin said that although
France should keep an impartial policy between the conflicting
sides in the Middle East, it should not be too soft towards those
who are resorting to violence.
</P>
<P>
"We should prove a policy of balance, but we should not be
indulgent with those who use violence. That does not reinforce the
position of France, which can only be weakened in the balance of
force with violence and fanaticism," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Being impartial should not mean being blind to the dangerous
acts for the fragile peace process," said the prime minister.
</P>
