<HEADLINE> Departing U.N. Humanitarian Coordinator to Brief Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The departing U.N.
humanitarian coordinator in Iraq, Von Sponeck, would brief the
United Nations Security Council on the U.N. oil-for-food program
in Iraq Tuesday afternoon, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said it would be an informal briefing.
</P>
<P>
Sponeck, who was appointed to the post in September 1998, the
fifth humanitarian coordinator to run the program, will leave the
job on March 31 to protest the nine-year-long sanctions against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sponeck met U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Monday and he
also briefed the U.N. chief on the implementation of the
humanitarian program in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Annan issued a statement after the meeting which said, "The
secretary-general made clear, and Mr. Von Sponeck fully understood,
that United Nations policy on the oil-for-food program is set by
the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
Annan also said in the statement that he shared the views of Von
Sponeck on how to make the program more effective and beneficial
for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general will review those ideas critically with
all concerned," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Sponeck has on occasions criticized the U.N. sanctions against
Iraq, saying it has resulted in "a true human tragedy" and the oil-
for-food program was not even meeting the minimum requirements of
the Iraqi people. He urged the lifting of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Some of the Security Council members have expressed their deep
concern on the failure of the program which began to be
implemented in late 1996. 
</P>
