<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: U.N. Steps Up Relief Efforts in Flood-Hit Mozambique (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations,
concerned over the worsening flooding situation in Mozambique,
has responded with strengthened efforts to seek more funds and
helicopters for the Southern African country in a bid to assist
Maputo in fighting against the nation's worst flooding in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
U.N. agencies Tuesday appealed for more helicopters and other
emergency aid for Mozambique, where up to 100,000 people have yet
to be evacuated from rising waters bearing diseases including
cholera.
</P>
<P>
The Rome-based United Nations World Food Program (WFP) warned
Tuesday that the situation for hundreds of thousands of
Mozambicans stranded by recent floods and cyclones is worsening
and that people will increasingly run the risk of illness and
starvation if humanitarian assistance is not immediately expanded,
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said here.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries pledged 13.5 million U.S. dollars at emergency
talks in Geneva. Italy and the Netherlands led the pledges with 5
million U.S. dollars and 3.15 million U.S. dollars respectively,
followed by Portugal with 2 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Aircraft supplied by South Africa have rescued some 4,000
people since Sunday. But air power is severely lacking, especially
helicopters which can swoop down and carry 50 to 60 people at a
time, according to U.N. relief agencies.
</P>
<P>
"The message is there are not enough helicopters and more are
needed. The number of helicopters being used there now is not
enough to evacuate all he people hanging onto trees," said
Christiane Berthaiaume of the WFP. "It is a race against time, a
question of days and hours. The situation has become particularly
difficult since the weekend when the Limpopo River banks
overflowed again."
</P>
<P>
Over the past five days, an additional four to eight meters of
flood waters have engulfed the African country's hardest hit areas
caused by an overflowing of dams in Southern Africa and Zimbabwe.
And the opening of the spillway gates of the Kariba dam on the
Zambezi River Monday will cause further flooding, reports said.
</P>
<P>
In response to the growing crisis, the WFP is launching a
massive emergency aid operation for the country -- and potentially
the region. The food aid agency already estimates that immediate
support is required to search, rescue and care for up to 300,000
people.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations appealed last week for 13.6 million U.S.
dollars to help 300,000 people for six months with food assistance,
shelter, health care, water, sanitation and education.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs
announced that a second five-member U.N. Disaster Assessment
Coordination Team was deployed Tuesday morning and is scheduled to
arrive in Maputo, capital of Mozambique, Tuesday in what came as
the strengthened U.N. efforts to assist the African country to
fight against floods, the worst in 30 years, Eckhard said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Also Monday, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan asked Ross
Mountain, the assistant emergency relief coordinator, to travel
immediately to Mozambique to serve as his special humanitarian
envoy to the country. He also authorized the release of resources
from the Central Emergency Revolving Fund to reinforce the
continuing relief efforts being undertaken by U.N. agencies on the
ground, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
At least 350 people have died, more than 650,000 have been
made homeless and crops vital for surviving the coming winter
have been swept away in Mozambique, South Africa, Zimbabwe and
Botswana in three weeks of flooding.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican disaster officials said the situation was much
worse than the WFP's estimates. Up to 900,000 people needed urgent
aid, they said. The government has said it will need 65 million U.
S. dollars to rebuild flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Greg Harti, spokesman for the World Health Organization (WHO)
in Geneva, said that flooding and contamination of drinking water
supplies increased the risk of outbreaks of disease.
</P>
<P>
"Cholera is a big concern. Malaria will become an increasing
concern as flood waters recede and stagnate. Dysentery, obviously,
is already a concern," Harti said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
