<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Digital Technology Paints Pictures of World's Forest Under Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The maps and reports reveal widespread logging in the forests
of the Congo Basin, and extensive mining, energy and road
construction projects in the forests of Canada.
</P>
<P>
"Two years ago, we documented that only a fifth of the world's
historic forest cover remains as frontier forests or large tracts
of intact forests. At the current rate of expansion, we estimated
that another 40 percent would be lost in the next 10 to 20 years,"
said Dirk Bryant, director of Global Forest Watch, an initiative
of the Washington, DC-based World Resources Institute.
</P>
<P>
"It now looks like we have underestimated those threats in some
places," Bryant added.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, researchers at the World Resources
Institute and World Forest Watch are able to map out logging
across the Congo Basin, a region that contains the world's second
largest continuous tropical forest after the Amazon, thanks to a
unique technology combination of satellite imagery, geographic
information system (GIS) and mapping software.
</P>
<P>
The digital and remote sensing technology, along with the
Internet and on-the-ground observation, will help provide accurate
forest information to anyone with access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
It also enables governments to better manage their forests, and
provides local groups with the information they will need to
participate in the management of their forests.
</P>
<P>
Global Forest Watch currently has 75 partners in seven
countries. During the next five years, the international network
will span 21 countries and cover 80 percent of the world's
remaining frontier forests.
</P>
<P>
It has received support from both environmental groups and
industry. Software companies such as Environmental Systems
Research Institute, and home furnishings company, IKEA, have given
major donations to support Global Forest Watch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
