<HEADLINE> Alitalia-KLM-Northwest Takes Off on April 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The new air transport alliance
between the Italian national carrier Alitalia, KLM of the
Netherlands and Northwest Airlines of the United States will
officially take off on April 2 with code-sharing and common
frequent flier programs.
</P>
<P>
The alliance between the three airlines will initially service
42 cities in Europe, the Middle East, Africa and the United States
and work out of the air hubs of Fiumicino in Rome, Milan's
Malpensa, Detroit and Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
The first new initiative of the alliance, in the future to be
known as Wings, will be the start-up of non-stop service by
Northwest between Detroit and Rome, Detroit and Milan.
</P>
<P>
The code-sharing agreement will be extended from the flights
themselves to on-ground services for check-in, reservations and
sales and all frequent flier programs will be merged as of April 2.
</P>
<P>
The Alitalia-KLM-Northwest alliance received an green light
from European Commission anti-trust authorities in December 1999,
while Northwest and KLM have been working together since 1993 with
common flights, frequent flier programs, business class services
and waiting rooms.
</P>
<P>
Together, the Wings alliance between the three carriers will
carry some 90 million passengers a year at the last count, with 50
million from Northwest, 24 million from Alitalia and 15 million
from KLM.
</P>
<P>
The alliance creates Europe's largest airline in terms of
passengers transported in 1998, serving 377 destinations in 87
countries. It will use over 672 planes (148 from Alitalia, 405
from Northwest and 119 from KLM), employ about 94,000 people and
should see a turnover of 20 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Northwest is the world's fourth largest airline with 1,700
flights daily serving Detroit, Minneapolis-St.Paul, Memphis, Tokyo
and Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
Alitalia serves 130 cities in 63 nations out of Rome's
Fiumicino airport and Milan's Malpensa airport while KLM, with its
partners, serves over 500 cities in 100 countries on six
continents.
</P>
<P>
Alitalia-KLM-Northwest are currently negotiating to bring Thai
Airlines into their alliance in order to expand in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
