<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Slips In February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer confidence
slipped in February from an all-time high in January due to higher
interest rates and oil prices, the Conference Board said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board, a prominent research group, said in a
report that the Consumer Confidence Index now stands at 141.8,
down from 144.7 in January.
</P>
<P>
"Declining consumers' expectations for the next six months was
the major reason for the overall dip in confidence," said Lynn
Franco, director of the Conference Board's Consumer Research
Center. "Consumer attitudes will bear watching over the next few
months to gauge the impact of rising interest rates and relatively
high gas prices. As for now, the index is signaling further
economic growth ahead."
</P>
<P>
The report said the percentage of respondents who rated
business conditions as "good" fell to 46.2 percent, down from 47.3
percent in January. Consumers holding the opposite view increased
to 8.8 percent, up from 8.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of consumers who say jobs are "plentiful" slipped to
51.2 percent from 55.2 percent in the previous survey, it added.
</P>
<P>
The consumers are less optimistic about the short-term business
outlook, the report said, adding that the percentage expecting
business conditions to improve over the next six months dropped to
17.6 percent from 20 percent and the proportion expecting
conditions to worsen rose to 4.7 percent from 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The consumer confidence index is closely watched because
consumer spending makes up about two-thirds of the U.S. economic
activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
