<HEADLINE> OAU Donates Half Million U.S. Dollars to Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of
African Unity (OAU) Monday donated 500,000 U.S. dollars to
Mozambique to help the country cope with devastating floods.
</P>
<P>
OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim handed over a cheque of
500,000 dollars to permanent representative of Mozambique to the
OAU, Alexandre Zandamela.
</P>
<P>
"The contribution is a clear and firm expression of our sense
of concern and solidarity with the people of Mozambique," Salim
said.
</P>
<P>
Cyclone Eline swept southern Africa last week. A combination
of destructive cyclone, heavy rain storm, over-flowing rivers and
floods have reportedly claimed hundreds of Mozambicans' lives, and
make hundreds of thousands of people homeless.
</P>
<P>
At least 65.5 million dollars are needed for the rescue
operation, according to Zandamela, who is also Mozambican
Ambassador to Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Stressing African solidarity in action, Salim appealed to
African and non-African heads of state and government to provide
and increase whatever support they can give to the people of
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that South Africa, Botswana and Malawi have
offered the Mozambican government logistic support, including
helicopters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
