<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Agrees to Ratify SADC Tourism Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Parliament Tuesday
agreed to ratify the protocol on tourism in the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) allowing for the adoption of a
regional approach to promoting tourism.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was crafted in line with international travel
trends that show tourists normally visit more than one country,
said Zimbabwe's Mines, Environment and Tourism Minister Simon
Moyo.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, a regional approach to promote and integrate the
regional tourism policies can only accelerate the development and
growth of the tourism sector in member countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Regional Tourism Organization of Southern Africa had
earlier launched a regional directory featuring various tourism
attractions of the region.
</P>
<P>
"Member states have recognized that a thriving tourism sector
can contribute to economic development as evidenced by the fact
that tourism has remained the fastest growing sector in the
region, despite the harsh economic environment we are facing,"
Moyo said.
</P>
<P>
In implementing the protocol, the minister said, member
countries would have to harmonize their national policies,
strategies and programs.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation among member states would extend to research and
making available national facilities for promotion of tourism
opportunities, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe would gain tremendously from the cooperation
because other countries in the region are much more advanced in
the areas of marketing, human resources, research and product
development.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe will take advantage in training its work force and at
the same time tap research data, which will improve local tourism
operations," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
