<HEADLINE> Iran Accuses U.S. of Aggravating Pollution in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Navy Commander Rear
Admiral Abbas Mohtaj on Tuesday accused the U.S. of aggravating the
environmental pollution in the Gulf by deploying military forces in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The dozens of U.S. warships and nuclear-powered submarines are
responsible for the various kinds of radioactive, chemical, thermal
and sound pollution in the Gulf, Mohtaj said on the sidelines of
the 10-day "Vahdat (Unity) 78" war games in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. navy carried out unconventional exercises
in the Gulf, leaving behind irreparable damage to the environment,
the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Mohtaj said the ammunition fired by the U.S. navy in its
maneuvers including depleted uranium has severely threatened the
health of the people living in the region.
</P>
<P>
The cases of cancer in Iraq has risen tenfold since the Gulf War
in 1991, he said, and 200,000 out of 700,000 U.S. forces who took
part in the Gulf War are suffering from the uranium-related
infection known as the "Gulf Syndrome."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian commander urged the regional countries to protect
the environment of the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the ongoing maneuvers conducted jointly by the army
and the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC), Mohtaj said the
Iranian navy gives due consideration to safeguarding the
environment in its exercises and it even refrains from using live
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to the Iranian navy's exercises, the regional
states can make use of Iran's experience in protection of the
environment of the Persian Gulf," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the naval forces of the Iranian army and the IRGC have
conducted three phases of the "Vahdat 78" exercises in the Gulf,
which was kicked off on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The maneuver was scheduled in five stages in an area of 64,000
square kilometers with participation of 60 vessels, 120 gunboats,
30 helicopters, 15 warplanes and several submarines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
