<HEADLINE> Arafat: Israel Responsible for Deadlocked Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat said on Tuesday the Israeli government
is fully responsible for the stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference held here with visiting President of
the European Commission (EC) Romano Prodi, Arafat said the Israeli
side alone is to be blamed for the current crisis in the talks
because it is not committed to the implementation of the Sharm el
Sheikh memorandum signed last September.
</P>
<P>
Arafat praised Europe's role in the peace-making efforts in the
region and expressed appreciation for the support which the
European Union (EU) extended to the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
He also highlighted the importance of activating Europe's role
in moving forward the peace process which ground to a halt earlier
this month over a long-delayed Israeli troops withdrawal from 6.1
percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Prodi, a former Italian prime minister, promised
that Europe would continue to play its role in the peace process
and support the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
During their talks held Tuesday morning, Arafat and Prodi
discussed the Mideast peace process and bilateral relations. Prodi
is expected to end his tour in the Gaza Strip later Tuesday after
visiting Palestinian refugee camps and the European hospital funded
by the EU.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Palestinian Minister of Planning and
International Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath also criticized Israel for
trying to block Prodi's visit to East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Voice of Palestine radio, Sha'ath stressed
that the Palestinians viewed those visits made by international
officials to East Jerusalem as an expression of support for and
solidarity with the Palestinians' legitimate rights over the city.
</P>
<P>
And their talks with PLO Minister for Jerusalem Affairs Faisal
Husseini would also help the Palestinians reclaim their sovereignty
over the holy city under the relevant U.N. resolutions, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
He said any official who is unwilling to visit East Jerusalem
will not be received elsewhere since this is regarded as a denial
of the Palestinians' political, historical and religious rights.
</P>
<P>
Israeli authorities had reportedly tried to prevent Prodi from
visiting East Jerusalem. But the attempt was foiled after Prodi
held talks with Husseini at the Ecole Publiqe school on the latest
developments of the Palestinian-Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
Prodi arrived in Israel on Sunday on a two-day visit, his first
visit to the region as president of the European Commission which
is the executive arm of the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
