<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq said it has cut its oil production by 300,000
barrels per day and the output will see further decrease if it can
not receive the long-awaited and direly-needed spare parts for its
dilapidated oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammad Mehdi Salah has recently confirmed
that Iraq has sold 23 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil in the past
three years, with only 6 billion dollars going to Iraq's hands.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Tourism Mamdouh Beltagui the
Tourism Ministry will open on Wednesday the first Egyptian tourist
fair in Nasr City, the economic daily Al Alam Elyom reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said tourist delegations from 20 countries and 1,000
travel agencies from 86 states will participate in three-day fair
that is under the title of fair and market of travel to the
Mediterranean Sea in 2000.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the fair, a tourist-related show covering an
area of 5,000 square meters will be held with 130 display pavilions
from 26 countries around the world.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey is making great efforts to promote the use of
thermal energy in home heating in its third largest city of Izmir,
reported Turkish Daily News on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Izmir's Balcova District Mayor Ali Lhsan Ulker announced that
the number of people using thermal energy will be increased from
the current 4,000 to 20,000 through a new project. New thermal
wells will be dug under the project, which will be funded by the
Izmir's Governor's Office.
</P>
<P>
Balcova is Izmir's thermal energy center. The Izmir Municipality
intends to expand the use of thermal energy for heating all
buildings in the Balcova District and then the rest of Izmir.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, poor in fossil energy resources, plans to use thermal
and nuclear energy as alternatives, which are also cheaper and
healthier.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey has approved a protocol regarding agreements
reached at the fourth-term meeting of the Turkey-Bulgaria Joint
Industries Working Group, reported Turkish Daily News on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The protocol identified foodstuff, textile and electrical
household appliance industries as key sectors with regard to trade
between Turkey and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
It also highlighted the importance of small and medium-sized
business.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish Transport Ministry plans to put up a
tender this week to sell two new GSM network licences, priced at
650 million U.S. dollars, to private sector, reported Turkish Daily
News on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's anti-cartel watchdog, the Competition Board, is
expected Tuesday to reveal its rule on tender specifications
concerning the two mobile phone GSM network licenses.
</P>
<P>
A third licence to be issued will be operated by state-owned
telecommunications company Turk Telekom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
