<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli President Opposes Likud's Bill on Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer
Weizman Tuesday expressed his opposition to a Likud bill requiring
a special majority of registered voters in any national referendum
to approve an Israeli-Syrian peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said the referendum should be free and the bill,
presented by Likud Knesset (Parliament) member Silvan Shalom,
places prior restrictions on the vote in an attempt to defeat a
possible peace deal with Syria, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
It was Weizman's first public announcement supporting the peace
process with Syria since he was under a criminal investigation over
his financial irregularities of accepting a large sum of cash gifts
from a French millionaire.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel's law, any decision by the government to
relinquish the Golan Heights, which it occupied in the 1967 Middle
East war, in exchange for a peace deal with Syria must be approved
by a vote in the Knesset and a referendum.
</P>
<P>
The Shalom bill requires 50 percent plus one of all eligible
voters in a national referendum, and then at least 61 MKs in the
120-member Knesset to vote in favor for ratifying such a treaty.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the proposal presented by the government requires a
simply majority of only participants in the referendum to approve a
peace agreement instead.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak has reiterated his commitment several
times to hold such a referendum once he reaches an agreement on the
negotiation table, believing that he will win a sweep victory in
the vote.
</P>
<P>
But the opposition Likud faction predicted that Barak would not
got majority in the referendum, while the point was also proved by
several opinion polls recently.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said last December that if the referendum failed to
ratify an Israeli-Syrian peace agreement, he would resign. His
stand immediately elicit calls for his ousting from a number of
MKs, accusing him of incorrectly favoring one side in a critical
question which had split the whole country.
</P>
<P>
The government had accused Likud's bill of racism as it attempts
to neutralize the vote of nearly one million Israeli Arab citizens,
who are supposed to endorse any peace deal with Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition held talks with Likud to bridge their gap
over the bills, but the negotiation collapsed last month. As a
result, both the government and the opposition bills are to be
brought before the Knesset in Wednesday's debate.
</P>
<P>
The government's worries about the fate of its referendum bill
aggravated Monday night because even three partners in its
coalition had expressed their support for the Likud's bill. During
a caucus held on Monday night, Yitzhak Levy, leader of the National
Religious Party, and Natan Sharansky, leader of Yisrael Ba'aliya,
had announced that their MKs will vote for the Likud's bill.
</P>
<P>
Although Eli Yishai, leader of orthodox religious party Shas,
had yet pronounced his opinion, but some Shas MKs had shown their
inclination to the Likud's bill. Shas spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia
Yosef will decide Shas's stand Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Barak is reportedly planning to convene all the coalition
leaders Wednesday morning to try to convince their support for the
government proposal.
</P>
<P>
Some analyst warned that even if the Likud's bill passed only
its preliminary reading, it would send a dangerous message to Syria
and the international community that Israel had no real intention
of peace.
</P>
<P>
Syria will hesitate much more to go back to the negotiation
table in such a situation, according to these analysts, because it
will worry that even a deal with Israel could be reached, Israel's
referendum would reject it and Syria would be seen as a peace
seeker whose outstretched hand is refused.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks, resumed last December after a
45-month break, hit a snag again earlier this year only after two
rounds of talks due to differences over Israeli troops withdrawal
form the Golan Heights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Foreign Minister Wraps DPRK Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) and Yugoslavia have agreed to enhance
mutual support and cooperation in the international arena.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique released Tuesday after Yugoslav Foreign
Minister Zivadin Jovanovic wrapped his DPRK visit, the two
countries expressed concern about the increasing complication of
the Kosovo issue, saying that the issue should be resolved in line
with U.N. resolution 1244.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two countries have agreed to make more active
contacts and exchanges in political, economic and other areas, and
actively cooperate in seeking just and peaceful solution to
international issues, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Jovanovic called on Supreme People's Assembly
Presidium  President Kim Yong Nam, Supreme People's Assembly
Chairman Choe Tae Bok and other leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav foreign minister left here Tuesday at the end of
their four-day visit to the DPRK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
