<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Firm on Austria Policy Despite Haider's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- France will not change its
policy of isolation toward Austria despite the resignation of the
leader of far-right Freedom Party, Joerg Haider, from his post in
the party.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said on
Tuesday that the resignation will not change France's evaluation
of or position on the coalition government in Vienna, which is
made of the Freedom Party and the conservative People's Party.
</P>
<P>
She also said that all the other 14 European Union countries
will maintain their decided measures against Austria, which
includes a suspension of bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"These measures are targeted toward the government ... and not
the person of Mr. Haider," said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
Haider resigned from the presidency of Freedom Party on Monday
after the new Austrian government triggered a wave of condemnation
and protest abroad.
</P>
<P>
But the move by the Freedom Party leader is widely considered
as a tactic to alleviate the pressure on Austria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
