<HEADLINE> Today's Diplomatic News Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua)-- The following are highlights of
China's diplomatic news items today:
</P>
<P>
Military Leaders Meet U.S. Pacific Commander
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian stressed today during a
meeting with Dennis Blair, commander-in-chief of the pacific
command of the United States armed forces, that China's basic
policy toward the Taiwan issue remains "peaceful reunification and
'one country, two systems'", but that China will never commit
itself to giving up the use of force.
</P>
<P>
Chi said that the white paper "The One-China Principle and the
Taiwan Issue" had made clear the consistent stand of the Chinese
government toward the issue of Taiwan and reflected the common
aspiration of the entire Chinese people. The reunification cause
of China is irreversible, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Blair's delegation marks the first senior U.S. military
delegation to officially visit China since the U.S.-led NATO
bombed the Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia last May.
</P>
<P>
Blair reiterated that the two countries share common interest
in maintaining peace and development in the Asia-Pacific region
and even the whole world. He also stated that U.S. will stick to
the One-China policy.
</P>
<P>
-- Fu Quanyou, Chief of the General Staff of the People's
Liberation Army (PLA) of China, warned today while meeting with
Blair that the U.S. government should not let the Sino-U.S.
relations and bilateral military ties which have shown a trend of
resumption and improvement suffer from setbacks once again.
</P>
<P>
Fu said that Sino-U.S. relations is now at an important period
which faces both opportunities for improvement and development,
and problems calling for urgent and proper handling, and the
Taiwan issue is a key one.
</P>
<P>
 FM Spokesman on U.S. Human Rights Report
</P>
<P>
-- It is entirely unjustified for the U.S. State Department to
make allegations, regardless of the fact, about the human rights
situation in Hong Kong in its annual human rights report, Chinese
Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said here today.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the U.S. report, Zhu said that it has
met with criticism from the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) government and people from all walks of life in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"This is a fact generally recognized by the international
community and it is most inappropriate for the U.S. to make
uninvited remarks on and unwarranted interference in Hong Kong's
internal affairs," Zhu noted.
</P>
<P>
"We express our firm opposition to that," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
