<HEADLINE> HKTA Outlines Tourism Vision For 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Continued growth in visitor
arrivals is expected in 2000, with a forecast increase of 6.8
percent over 1999 to around 11.4 million, Amy Chan, executive
director of the Hong Kong Tourist Association (HKTA), said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a media briefing, Chan said priority would be strong
marketing of the diversity of Hong Kong's attractions in incentive,
convention, exhibition, business and inland markets in the future.
</P>
<P>
HKTA's plans for 2000 and beyond are a vision shared with the
Commission on Strategic Development, as outlined in the document
Bring the Vision to Life, said Chan.
</P>
<P>
She said HKTA has established three key platforms for 2000 --
to promote Hong Kong as the pre-eminent international and
cosmopolitan city in Asia, as the preferred gateway to the Chinese
inland areas and other parts of Asia, and as the entertainment,
media and events capital of the region.
</P>
<P>
While 75 percent of visitors are currently from Asia, a more
balanced ratio would be needed in order for Hong Kong to maintain
its reputation as a truly international city, she noted, adding
that HKTA would shift its marketing resources accordingly, with
particular emphasis directed at the North American and European
markets.
</P>
<P>
To cater to these markets, HKTA has embarked on a series of
global media alliances, such as the National Geographic, to attain
a broader reach and to deliver fresh aspects of the City of Life
program launched to promote Hong Kong through television, print
and Internet.
</P>
<P>
For the Chinese mainland that is one of the most important
markets of Hong Kong, HKTA will also establish closer partnerships
with provinces such as Yunnan and Sichuan and cities such as
Beijing and Guilin.
</P>
<P>
Chan said Hong Kong must also have in view the need to raise
service standards and develop new skills to meet the challenges
ahead.
</P>
<P>
Since the Quality Tourism Services scheme was launched last
year, over 166 retail and food beverage outlets representing 400
stores have applied to participate in the scheme, she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
