<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Gov't Gains 86.8 Mln Dollars At Land Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Three government lots were
sold for a total of 677.2 million HK dollars (about 86.8 million U.
S. dollars) at a public auction held by the Lands Department of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The land auction, which is the last one in the 1999/2000 fiscal
year, consisted of two lots designated for private residential
purposes on the Hong Kong Island and one for non-industrial uses
on Lantau Island of the New Territories.
</P>
<P>
Located on the Peak of the Hong Kong Island, the 13,570-square-
meter luxury site was the focus of the bidding and was sold for
490 million HK dollars (about 62.8 million U.S. dollars), 40
percent higher than the opening bid of 350 million HK dollars (
about 44.9 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second lot, which is about 880.8 square meters at Shau Kei
Wan on the Hong Kong Island, was sold for 170 million HK dollars (
about 21.8 million U.S. dollars). The opening bid was 110 million
HK dollars (about 14.1 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The third site on Lantau Island of the New Territories was sold
for 17.2 million HK dollars (about 2.2 million U.S. dollars), 2.8
times as much as the opening bid of 6 million HK dollars (about
769,230 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the results were within the market expectation
and investors are optimistic about a stable property market.
</P>
<P>
The site on Lantau Island, which was considered the most
successful deal at the auction, reflects investors' confidence
about the prospects of tourist development, they added.
</P>
<P>
The auction drew participation of mainly small and medium-sized
developers, while large developers are preparing for the future
land auctions as the government is expected to put more land on
sale in following fiscal years.
</P>
<P>
Acting Secretary for Planning and Lands Patrick Lau Lai-chiu on
Tuesday announced the Land Sale Program from April 2000 to March
2001, and the Land Development Program from April 2001 to March
2005.
</P>
<P>
For the 12 months from April 2000 to March 2001, public
auctions and tenders will be conducted according to a land sale
timetable to make available a total of 16 hectares of land for
private housing, 6 hectares for the Private Sector Participation
Scheme (PSPS) and 0.5 hectare for non-housing uses.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 16 hectares of land for private housing and 9
hectares for non-housing uses will be available for application in
the same period. Another 69 hectares of land will be available for
disposal by way of private treaty, comprising 58 hectares for
private housing and 11 hectares for non-housing uses.
</P>
<P>
"Altogether, 90 hectares of land for private housing will be
available for disposal in 2000/2001, compared with 52 hectares in
1999/2000," Lau said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Land Development Program for the four years from
April 2001 to March 2005, 333 hectares for private housing will be
available.  
</P>
</TEXT>
