<HEADLINE> Estrada Declares 2000 As Year of OFWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- In recognition of the pivotal
role played by the country's migrant workers in strengthening the
economy, Philippine President Joseph Estrada has declared 2000 as
the Year of the Overseas Filipino Workers (OFWs).
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Palace said Tuesday that Estrada issued a
proclamation before he left for Mindanao, the southern Philippines,
hailing the OFWs as the country's modern-day heroes "because of
their exemplary qualities of hard work, determination and self-
sacrifice."
</P>
<P>
He said that OFWs deserve to be recognized and honored for all
these qualities, as well as for their effective role and
contribution to the Philippines' efforts towards globalization.
</P>
<P>
"I call upon all government agencies, concerned non-
governmental organizations and the citizenry to lend their full
support and cooperation in the observance of the year of overseas
Filipino workers," Estrada said in his proclamation.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said OFWs play a "very important role" in reinforcing
the country's foreign currency reserves by way of remitting
portions of their dollar earnings into the country's banking
system.
</P>
<P>
This "alleviates the economic turbulence being experienced" by
the Philippines as a result of the world's ever changing economic
pattern, he said.
</P>
<P>
The country's OFWs, he added, also significantly contributed to
helping the Philippines hurdle the Asian financial crisis through
their annual dollar remittances.
</P>
<P>
"Sacrificing the comforts of home and their loved ones, these
modern-day heroes fostered goodwill among many countries in the
world and placed the Philippines in the international arena as a
leading supplier of skilled manpower," Estrada said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
