<HEADLINE> Uganda Hopes to Learn From China in Fight Against Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government said
that it hopes to learn from China in fighting corruption among
government officials and sensitizing the general public in the
same field.
</P>
<P>
Miria Matembe, Ugandan Minister of Ethics and Integrity, made
the remarks here on Tuesday afternoon when meeting with a
five-member delegation from the Chinese Ministry of Supervision.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation headed by Secretary-General of Ministry
of Supervision Yuan Chunqing arrived here Monday for a five-day
visit to the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Matembe said that the two countries have different systems in
fighting corruption, but they can exchange their experience in the
field by enhancing exchange visits. She stressed that Uganda is
determined to uproot rampant corruption through concerted efforts
by relevant ministries.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Yuan introduced China's experience and
achievement in fighting corruption and in enhancing public
awareness about the issue.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is ranked one of the most corrupt countries in the world
by Transparency International and more than 100 million U.S.
dollars, some 15 percent of the government's annual revenue, is
embezzled by corrupt officials each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
