<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Not to Change its Position on Austria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
on Tuesday that its position on Austria had not changed in the
wake of the resignation of Joerg Haider as the chief of Austria's
far-right Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
A commission spokesman said that the commission still shares
the concerns as demonstrated by Austria's 14 European Union (EU)
partners and the commission will continue to watch how the new
Austrian coalition government behaves.
</P>
<P>
"The commission's position has been consistent throughout,"
said the spokesman, who added that the commission will live up to
its expectation of serving as the guardian of the European Union
treaties.
</P>
<P>
The commission has earlier told Austria that no basic
principles of the treaties should be breached.
</P>
<P>
The same spokesman said that it was not up to the commission,
though the executive body of the 15-nation European Union, to
advise Austria what to do as an exit from the current political
plight.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen other EU members joined hands in isolating Austria
when Austria's new coalition government dominated by Haider's far-
right Freedom Party took power on February 4.
</P>
<P>
Haider, known for his non-tolerant and pro-nazism comments,
announced late on Monday the handover of the leadership of the
Freedom Party to Susanne Riess-Passer.
</P>
<P>
Riess-Passer is now serving as the vice-chancellor of the
Austrian coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Though not a member of the cabinet, Haider was the one who had
signed the preamble of the coalition government on behalf of the
Freedom Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
