<HEADLINE> EU Surprised by U.S. Opposition to IMF Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
expressed surprise on Tuesday at U.S. opposition to its German
candidate for the post of International Monetary Fund (IMF)
managing director.
</P>
<P>
Pedro Solbes, EU monetary affairs commissioner, said that it
came as a surprise what the Americans said about Caio Koch-Weser
not having the right qualifications.
</P>
<P>
"It makes no sense," said the commissioner, "He is very
experienced."
</P>
<P>
Solbes said the European Commission, the executive body of the
15-nation EU, would continue supporting the choice of Koch-Weser
as the EU candidate for the top IMF job.
</P>
<P>
At a European council meeting on Monday, EU finance ministers
unanimously agreed to back Koch-Weser for the post as IMF managing
director.
</P>
<P>
Koch-Weser, Germany's deputy finance minister, declared his bid
to replace the outgoing Michel Camdessus at the IMF helm three
months ago.
</P>
<P>
Competing with Koch-Weser for the top IMF job are two other
candidates -- the IMF's acting managing director Stanley Fischer
and Japanese finance ministry official Eisuke Sakakibara.
</P>
<P>
The executive board of the IMF met on Tuesday in Washington for
an informal discussion on the candidates before appointing the
managing director. 
</P>
