<HEADLINE> N.Irish Peace Rescue Plan Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 29 (Xinhua) -- One of the smaller pro-peace
agreement parties in Northern Ireland's suspended assembly has
launched a plan aimed at rescuing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The cross-community Alliance Party is urging all pro-agreement
parties to join together to call on all paramilitary groups to
make concessions on the arms issue, the BBC reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The party's six-point plan involves all of the pro-agreement
parties re-committing themselves to the Good Friday Agreement
signed in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
It called the paramilitary groups to renounce violence and
renew the talks with the disarmament commission, and also urged
normalization measures by the security forces, end of the
assembly's suspension and a day of reconciliation for republicans
and loyalists to start decommissioning their weapons.
</P>
<P>
The plan has been presented to the British, Irish and U.S.
governments.
</P>
<P>
The power-sharing executive set up last December was suspended
on February 11 due to the impasse over paramilitary weapons.
</P>
<P>
Alliance deputy leader Seamus Close said he believed that the
plan would relieve the pressure on Sinn Fein and strengthen its
hand in convincing the Irish Republican Army to return to talks
with the disarmament commission headed by General John de
Chastelain.
</P>
<P>
"This would show that no party had a special responsibility,
and would also be a tremendous confidence-building measure," the
Lagan Valley assembly member said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
