<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Fiscal 2000 Budget Approved By Lower House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Representatives,
or lower house, on Tuesday approved a record-high 84.99 trillion
yen (770.9 billion U.S. dollars) national budget for the fiscal
year of 2000, featuring measures designed to get Japan's economy
back to sustained growth.
</P>
<P>
The budget is certain to be enacted before the current fiscal
year ends on March 31 as the Japanese constitution rules that the
budget will automatically become law 30 days after the passage by
the lower house passage, even if the House of Councillors fails to
approve it.
</P>
<P>
The general-account budget for the year starting April 1, which
was submitted to the Diet (parliament) on January 28, was approved
by a majority vote with the support of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) and its two coalition partners, the Liberal
Party (LP) and New Komeito party.
</P>
<P>
The budget features a 2.6-percent expansion in general
expenditures to a record 48,091.4 billion yen (436.2 billion
dollars) in funding public works and other policy-oriented
projects.
</P>
<P>
The expansionary fiscal policy is designed to meet the Japanese
government's economic growth target of 1.0 percent in real terms
in fiscal 2000, which will be the second straight year of growth.
The government has voiced confidence that it will be able to
attain its goal of 0.6-percent growth for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
To help fund the budget, the Japanese government will have to
float a record 85.87 trillion yen (778.9 billion dollars) in bonds
during fiscal 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
