<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's January Unemployment Rate Stands at 4.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Japan's jobless rate for January
stood at a seasonally adjusted 4.7 percent, unchanged from the
revised figure for last December, the Management and Coordination
Agency said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate for men was 4.8 percent, 0.1 percent down over
last December, while that for women rose 0.1 percent to 4.5
percent in the month, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The number of unemployed Japanese increased by 110,000 from
last December to 3.09 million, rising above three million for the
first time in three months.
</P>
<P>
The agency, taking into account such elements as seasonal
factors, adjusted the jobless rates for June and July 1999 to 4.8
percent, rather than 4.9 percent, which was the worst rate ever
recorded in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Labor Ministry said in a separate report that
the ratio of job providers to job seekers in January stood at 0.52,
or 52 job providers for every 100 job seekers.
</P>
<P>
It was a rise from the 0.50 registered in December, marking the
third consecutive month of improvement.
</P>
<P>
The report said the number of people forced out of their jobs
due to bankruptcy or restructuring reached 1.01 million, an
increase of 10,000 compared with the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the employment statistics, Japanese Labor Minister
Takamori Makino said while the labor situation continued to be
severe, there were also a few bright signs including the increase
in overtime hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
