<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Expert Confirms Traces of South China Tigers in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Experts from the World
Wildlife Fund (WWF) today confirmed the credibility of traces of
South China tigers found in the eastern and southern region of
China and explained why sightings of the most endangered tiger
species have become more frequent.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Yu Changqing, director in charge of species and nature
reserve projects in WWF's China Program Office in Beijing, told
Xinhua today that the tiger trace reports in Hunan, Zhejiang and
Jiangxi provinces this year are credible, because they were proved
by Chinese wildlife experts with such scientific methods as
molecular genetic testing and DNA analysis of tiger droppings and
tiger hair.
</P>
<P>
He said that tigers become more daring when searching for food
in the spring, when food is hard to find and young tigers are
searching for mates.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, no living South China tigers
have been found in China since 1955, although there are 52 in
captivity. However, traces of the tigers in their natural habitats
in south China suggest that some 20-30 are living in the wild.
</P>
<P>
The more advanced methods used to identify their traces have
certainly aided the search for South China tigers, he added.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Lei Guangchun, another WWF expert, said it is easier to
spot tigers in the spring, because foliage where tigers are likely
to live is dry and sparse. The tigers' roars, which in the spring
are often mating calls, could also reveal their existence in
mountain areas.
</P>
<P>
The foundation plans to join with the Chinese Forestry
Administration to conduct a national investigation to locate the
remaining South China tigers.
</P>
<P>
The program, slated for March, will be based on experience from
WWF's cooperation with China in a Giant Panda Rescue Program,
which successfully rescued rare wildlife. WWF will help introduce
funding and advanced expertise for the program.
</P>
<P>
As the world's largest environmental organization, WWF started
its China programs in 1980, initially committed to the protection
of the giant panda. Its efforts have been gradually extended to
other programs such as the protection of wetlands and tropical
forests in China.
</P>
<P>
WWF recently gave priority to improving public awareness on
environmental protection in China. It noted that sightings of
tiger traces in recent years were all reported by local residents
in nature reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong to Expand Flower Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 29 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province will enlarge its planting area of flower industry to 66,
667 hectares in the next five years to achieve greater economic
efficiency from the sector.
</P>
<P>
A local official explained that as people's living standard
improves, the demand for fresh flowers has kept climbing rapidly
in China. Farmers in the province grew some 20,000 hectares of
flowers last year, and the output value was estimated at three
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has a mild climate all the year round and is frost-
free for the whole year, which has constituted Guangdong's
advantageous condition in growing flowers.
</P>
<P>
Local residents in this southern Chinese province all have a
tradition in growing and loving flowers. The recorded history of
flower growing in the province can be dated back to 111 years B.C
when people from Chencun of Shunde started to grow potted oranges
and flowers to greet the lunar Spring Festival -- an occasion for
family reunions.
</P>
<P>
After many years of development, flower growing has become a
professional industry which attracts overseas investors and
tourists alike, and spurs development of other businesses centered
on flowers.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the province is now home to 305
overseas-financed flower companies which have attracted about 300
million U.S. dollars of investment from overseas.
</P>
<P>
Many rural areas, which used to be very poor, have grown into a
galaxy of specialized centers in cultivating flowers and become
prosperous. Chinese and overseas tourists to Guangdong scramble
for having a look at the splendor of large number of flowers grown
at the centers.
</P>
<P>
Different kinds of scientific flower research organizations
have also mushroomed across the province.
</P>
<P>
Fresh and potted flowers grown by the province are sold to
different corners of China by air and are exported to more than
100 countries and regions. The Netherlands, the world's leading
fresh flower producer, imports more than 10 million U.S. dollars
worth of potted flowers from Guangdong each year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province earned well over 100 million U.S.
dollars from exporting flowers, accounting for a half of the
country's total flower exports, said the local sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
