<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Host Int'l Congress on Traditional Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- An international congress on
research and application of traditional medicine will be held in
the Chinese capital this April, it was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The International Congress on Traditional Medicine (Beijing
2000), co-sponsored by China's State Administration of Traditional
Chinese Medicine (SATCM) and the World Health Organization (WHO),
will be composed of policy-making forums, academic symposiums and
an exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Symposiums will mainly discuss newest findings of laboratory
and clinical research of disease treatment using traditional
medicine. The diseases range from cerebral and cardiovascular
diseases, rheumatism, diabetes, cancer, HIV/AIDS to old age-
related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
Other topics include modernization of traditional Chinese
medicine (TCM), new drug development, and non-drug therapies such
as acupuncture, massage and breathing exercise.
</P>
<P>
Health officials of 24 countries, and more than 1,100
specialists from about 30 countries and regions will participate,
making the conference the biggest of the kind in the world, Li
Zhenji, Vice-Chairman of the conference's organizing committee,
told a press conference this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is also deputy director of SATCM, said traditional
medicine is becoming more and more preferred globally. The WHO has
established 26 collaboration centers of traditional medicine
around the world, with seven in China.
</P>
<P>
"Having a long history of using TCM and as a key member country
of WHO, China has the duty to push forward global development of
traditional medicine," he said, adding that the country now has
some 2,600 TCM hospitals and more than 1,000 TCM manufacturers,
employing over one million people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
