<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Reports No Leap Y2K Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital of Beijing
sailed smoothly through the leap year computer bug, the municipal
government announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Public utilities, hospitals, transportation and
telecommunication sectors and other enterprises started reporting
to the city's millennium computer emergency center at 00:20 (local
time) today no glitches in computer operations.
</P>
<P>
The reports indicated that computers at all the sites shifted
smoothly from February 28 to 29, officials at the center said.
</P>
<P>
By 18:30, the center had received only two reports from
individuals that their personal computers encountered problems due
to wrong timing.
</P>
<P>
Early February 29 and March 1 are two sensitive times when
computers might fail to recognize February 29, 2000, and cause
problems, said Gao Zhichao, an engineer of the center.
</P>
<P>
However, early March 1 poses much less danger for computer foul-
ups than February 29, Gao said.
</P>
<P>
Also today, the center announced that so-called millennium bug
of computers has largely been tackled in the city.
</P>
<P>
From now on, it will focus on minor computer mishaps, such as
bugs in application programs that computer users may encounter.
</P>
</TEXT>
