<HEADLINE> Syrian Newspapers Demand Israeli Commitment to Golan Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Syrian newspapers on Tuesday
played down Israel's admission of a pledge made by former prime
minister Yitzhak Rabin to withdraw from occupied Syrian territory,
demanding an explicit commitment from Israel toward peace.
</P>
<P>
The official Tishrin (October) daily said in a commentary that
despite its significance, Rabin's pledge may not help revive the
Mideast peace process on the Syrian and Lebanese tracks unless it
is committed by the current Israeli government and accompanied by
tangible actions.
</P>
<P>
The paper said political observers suspect that Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's confession of the existence of Rabin's pledge
might be a manoeuvre aimed to mitigate Arab anger over the stalled
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials, including Barak, admitted Monday former
Israeli governments since that of Rabin have acknowledged the
principle of complete pullout from the Golan Heights which it
seized from Syria in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the disclosure, the paper said "the ambiguous and
mysterious statements do not convince anyone in Damascus or Beirut
or other Arab capitals" unless Barak's government is serious to
turn the pledge into reality.
</P>
<P>
Another official daily, Al Thawrah (Revolution), said the
revelation is still defect and incomplete unless it is accompanied
by a clear-cut Israeli commitment to halt to aggression.
</P>
<P>
Al Baath (Rejuvenation), daily of the ruling Socialist Arab
Party, said Rabin's pledge is an essential condition that Israel
should carry out to create the suitable circumstances for resuming
the stalled Syrian-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli talks have been postponed indefinitely after
two rounds of talks held in December and January, due to Damascus
insistence that Israel make a promise to return the Golan and
withdraw to the June 4, 1967 border line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
