<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Policemen Charged of Attacking Student Dorms Stand Trial in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran's military court on Tuesday
started open trial of the policemen who were charged of attacking
students in the Tehran University dormitory last July.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Tehran Military Prosecutor Houshang Eqbal accused 20
police commanders and personnel of attacking student dorms and
beating students, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The accused included former Tehran police commander Brigadier
General Farhad Nazari and commander of the special unit of the
Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) Colonel Jamshid
Khodabakhshi.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 20 accused, eight were from the IRGC special unit and
nine from the security forces or armed police, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Eqbal underlined the entry of policemen into a university
dormitory requires prior permission from the Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Anti-riot policemen stormed Tehran University dormitory on July
8 following a student protest against the approval of a bill by the
Majlis (parliament) to amend the country's press law with an aim to
tightening restrictions on the press.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian Supreme National Security Council,
three people, including a civilian opponent, a police officer and a
conscript of the IRGC were shot by bullets in the incident. The
conscript died in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
The police attack, without prior permission from the Interior
Ministry, triggered a week-long nationwide protest and political
disturbance in the country, the worst since the 1979 Islamic
revolution.
</P>
<P>
Iranian reformists have stated the attack was pre-arranged and
politically motivated with an aim to cracking down the freedom-
seeking movement in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mohsen Rahami, an attorney for the Tehran University and
students, said at the hearing session that commander Nazari said
before the attack that he had predicted the incident.
</P>
<P>
"It may safely be concluded that the attack on the dormitory was
pre-arranged and was waiting only for an excuse to justify it," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Rahami also called for an investigation into the assaults by
some civilians on students during the incident, saying that there
were some people who coordinated the civilian elements to work with
the military forces and had dispatched them to the dormitory to
beat up students.
</P>
<P>
He believed that there was a coordinating center behind the
dormitory beating. "In less than 24 hours after the incident, 204
students were arrested, some of whom were beaten," he added.
</P>
<P>
The attorney noted that in addition to the illegal entry of the
police into the dormitory, the accused also set fire on several
rooms, destroyed students' belongings and threw out a student from
the third floor.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some foreign students were also beaten and
injured, and were later forced to take refuge in their respective
embassies.
</P>
<P>
"The unfortunate incident destroyed the image of the Islamic
republic both inside and outside the country," Rahami said.
</P>
<P>
The next hearing on the case will be held on March 4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
