<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of India's 2000-01 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister
Yashwant Sinha presented the country's budget for the financial
year 2000-01 to the parliament here on Tuesday. Following are the
highlights of the budget:
</P>
<P>
-- Central Sector Plan Outlay to be increased from 1.03521
trillion rupees (24.07 billion U.S. dollars) to 1.17334 trillion
rupees (27.29 billion U.S. dollars);
</P>
<P>
-- Gross Budget support to the Plan to be increased from 770
billion rupees (17.91 billion U.S. dollars) to 881 billion rupees
(20.49 billion U.S. dollars);
</P>
<P>
-- Defense Allocation to be raised to 585.87 billion rupees (13.
62 billion U.S. dollars) from 456.94 billion rupees (10.63 billion
U.S. dollars);
</P>
<P>
-- Public Sector Undertakings (PSUs) which cannot be revived to
be closed down;
</P>
<P>
-- Government equity in all non-strategic PSUs to be brought
down to 26 percent and below;
</P>
<P>
-- Government not to close down any Public Sector Bank;
</P>
<P>
-- Banks to be allowed to raise capital from market to expand
operations and for meeting capital adequacy norms;
</P>
<P>
-- Potentially viable PSUs to be restructured and revived;
</P>
<P>
-- Workers' interests to be protected;
</P>
<P>
-- Speedy implementation of the National Highway Development
Project at a cost of 540 billion rupees (12.56 billion U.S.
dollars);
</P>
<P>
-- Progressive corporatization of public sector service
providers in areas like telecom, ports and airports;
</P>
<P>
-- 500 million rupees (11.63 million U.S. dollars) for New
Millennium Indian Technology Leadership Initiatives;
</P>
<P>
-- Year 2001 declared "Women's Empowerment Year"; and
</P>
<P>
-- A new Group Insurance Scheme "Janashree Bima Yojana" to be
introduced to provide social security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
