<HEADLINE> Lloyd Threatens to Take Legal Action  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Britain's former Davis Cup
captain David Lloyd threatened on Tuesday to take legal action
against the Lawn Tennis Association (LTA) for slander after he was
sacked for allegedly affecting team morale.
</P>
<P>
According to the BBC report, Lloyd, who was replaced on Monday
by former Wimbledon semifinalist Roger Taylor after publicly
criticizing two of his players, said: "That is a direct slander on
my character and future. They said my team had no spirit and no
morale."
</P>
<P>
"I will not stand by and let people make incorrect accusations.
</P>
<P>
"As far I am concerned we had fantastic team spirit and
fantastic team morale and that what's my future in life is all
about.
</P>
<P>
"If that's been put into jeopardy then I will take action.
There are no two ways about it," he said.
</P>
<P>
After Britain had been beaten 4-1 by the Czech Republic in
their world group tie this month, Lloyd said second string players
Arvind Parmar and Jamie Delgado were not fit enough to compete at
international level.
</P>
<P>
He also said it was the LTA's job to deliver players to him in
a fit condition.
</P>
<P>
LTA chief executive John Crowther said on Monday Lloyd had been
dismissed for his public criticism of the team and "the
unnecessary adverse affect these had on players and coaches
connected to the Davis Cup squad".
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday Crowther said former British number one Jeremy Bates
would coach the Davis Cup squad under Taylor's guidance.
</P>
<P>
"I can announce this morning that Jeremy Bates has been asked
by Roger to be the coach," Crowther said. "We are going to have
great team spirit and we are going to build on it from now."
</P>
<P>
Bates, 37, was consistently ranked as Britain's number one from
1988 to 1994 when he retired from international tennis.
</P>
<P>
He won the Wimbledon mixed doubles with Jo Durie in 1987 and
reached the final 16 in the men's singles in 1992. 
</P>
