<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Reforms For SOEs in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Liu Hong, director of the
National Bureau of Statistics (NBS), told a press conference
Monday that China will meet the target of turning money-losing
State-owned enterprises (SOEs) into profit enterprises by the end
of this year as part of a three-year reform plan.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by NBS Monday, profits of large
and medium-sized SOEs increased by 77.7 percent in 1999. Losses
dropped 15.9 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that apart from two loss-making industries - military
and coal - the 14 industrial sectors in China began to turn around
and make profits last year.
</P>
<P>
At local levels, SOEs in 20 of the 30 provinces, municipalities
and autonomous regions are now turned out of their loss-making
cycle.
</P>
<P>
Since January, such major economic indicators as industrial
output, foreign trade volume, consumer prices and direct foreign
investment have begun rising.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will continue to pursue a pro-active
fiscal policy and implement the strategy of developing China's
western region this year.
</P>
<P>
Liu predicts that this year's economic growth will exceed the
rate of 7.1 percent in 1999 and create favorable conditions for
the SOEs in overcoming existing difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The success of the three-year plan to revive SOEs should not
only depend on reducing the proportion of money-losing enterprises,
Liu said, adding that the success of the plan is also due to the
healthy turn around of SOEs that suffered the biggest losses.
</P>
<P>
Chen Qingtai, an economist from the Development Research Center
of the State Council, said that the main focus of the three-year
plan is to reform SOEs, gain valuable experience from
restructuring the industry, capital circulation and relocation of
workers.
</P>
<P>
Major reforms can be seen in the government's decision to
concentrate on some key sectors and enterprises. The government
will also allow private capital to be injected into many
previously government-dominated areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Reforms For SOEs in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has begun to reduce government shares in State-owned
companies on a trial basis. For example, from 2000, Beijing will
not allow the establishment of any solely-owned SOEs in industrial
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of such large enterprise groups such as China
Petroleum Co. Ltd. witnessed a new stage in restructuring SOEs.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of a modern corporate system has also made
new progress. Local governments in northeast China's Jilin and
Liaoning provinces, for example, have set up independent share-
holding companies which no longer allow administrative authorities
to directly running SOEs.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai and Zhejiang have experimented with setting up an
external supervision council and financial auditors for SOEs.
China has also began to establish an incentive and supervision
system of corporate leaders.
</P>
<P>
In the last three years, the Chinese government has focused on
resolving a number of prominent problems in SOEs, including
excessive debts, outdated technology, waste of resources and
environment pollution.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, 73 large and medium-sized
SOEs performed debt-to-equity swaps in 1999, reducing debt by 111.
3 billion yuan. The government also wrote off more than seven
million yuan in bad loans of some 800 SOEs that went bankrupt last
year.
</P>
<P>
By scrapping cotton weaving production capacity by more than
nine million spindles over the last two years, the textile
industry became the first industrial sector to turn around their
loss-making cycle in 1999. Coal, metallurgical, building materials,
non-ferrous metal and petrol-chemical industries have also closed
down a great number of small factories that waste energy and
pollute the environment.
</P>
<P>
The government is developing social insurance systems,
increasing the income of medium- and low-income workers and
encouraging the expansion of private enterprises to accelerate
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
China's unemployment insurance system helps three million laid
off workers to find new jobs every year. The government is
planning to develop a complete social insurance and employment
benefit system in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Flourishing private companies have taken in many laid-off
workers from SOEs, re-employing 1.4 million of them in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Local economists say that the success of the three-year plan of
reviving SOEs is crucial for China's economic reform and future
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0130 </DOCNO>
