<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Reacts Cautiously to Haider's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Israel will assess the
resignation of Austrian far-right leader Joerg Haider before making
any decision on whether to send its ambassador back to Vienna,
Israeli Foreign Ministry said Tuesday in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Haider, an outspoken xenophobe and sympathizer of the Nazis,
announced his stepping down as leader of the Freedom Party late
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The 50-year-old populist handed over his mace to his party
colleague Susanne Riess-Passer, currently vice-chancellor in the
government headed by Chancellor Wolfgang Schuessel, leader of the
conservative People's Party.
</P>
<P>
Haider's dramatic resignation was considered as an effort to
reduce the storm of international pressure on Austria and help the
coalition function more smoothly.
</P>
<P>
However, some analysts in Jerusalem pointed out Haider's
comments that he will remain active in national politics, saying
the move is just another trick of Haider to boost his popularity.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of the Freedom Party in Austria's new coalition
government earlier in the month - although Haider himself did not
occupy a cabinet post - has made all other 14 European Union
members freeze their bilateral contacts with Vienna.
</P>
<P>
In protest against Haider's praise of Hitler's policies and his
description of Nazi veterans as "men of good character," Israeli
Foreign Ministry announced the recall of its ambassador from
Vienna, one of the harshest gestures in the diplomatic arena,
shortly after the new Austrian government was sworn in.
</P>
<P>
"Israel cannot remain silent in the face of the rise of
extremist right-wing parties, in particular in those countries
which played a role in the events that brought about the
eradication of a third of the Jewish people in the Holocaust," the
ministry said then in a statement.
</P>
<P>
During the World War II, the Nazi regime deliberately carried
out a systematic liquidation of the Jewish community in Europe, in
which some 6 million Jews, including 1.5 million children, were
slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
Haider has repeatedly apologized for his controversial comments
since his Freedom Party drew international attention after ranking
second in Austria's parliamentary election last October.
</P>
<P>
He even signed a declaration renouncing Austria's Nazi past and
affirming his commitment to the values of democracy and human
rights in a bid to win approval of President Thomas Klestil for a
coalition including his party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
