<HEADLINE> Indonesia Needs Close Ties With East Timor: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia needs a close
relationship with East Timor, a former province of Indonesia, and
should build mutual cooperation in the future, a legislator said
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Economically, we can not expect anything from East Timor, but
we can be a good friend of East Timorese, and we can establish a
good relationship with them, and I think we should establish a
good relationship, because East Timor is our neighbor," Chairman
of the House of Representatives (DPR) Commission on Security and
Foreign Affairs Yasril Ananta Baharuddin told Xinhua in an
interview here on Tuesday when commenting on President Abdurrahman
Wahid's ongoing visit to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Politically, East Timor will be a strategic country for
Indonesia, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that East Timor needs to be proposed to join the
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations).
</P>
<P>
"And the relationship between Indonesia and East Timor should
balance and bring benefit to the two countries," Baharuddin said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Wahid, who was visiting in Dili, capital of
East Timor, said that the Indonesian government would give its
hand to help its former province.
</P>
<P>
"We will give whatever we can," said Wahid who is the first
Indonesian leader to visit East Timor since the territory
separated from Indonesia after a ballot last year.
</P>
<P>
East Timor voted in favor of independence in a U.N.-sponsored
direct ballot in August last year and separated from the unitary
state of Indonesia after 23 years of integration.
</P>
<P>
The territory is now under U.N. administration, before getting
a full independence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Grant Wilson, a liaison officer of the UNTAET (
United Nations Transition Administration in East Timor) in Jakarta,
told Xinhua that "it is important for Indonesia to establish close
relations with East Timor to show the world that Indonesia is a
democratic country."
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Indonesian government to support the
reconciliation process in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to Indonesian people to realize that East
Timor is a free (state) now. And I am very optimistic about the
bilateral relations between the two countries," Wilson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
