<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Sets Growth Target at 7 to 8 Pct for 2000-01 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 29 (Xinhua) -- India has set its economic
growth rate at seven to eight percent for the next financial year
beginning from April 1 with an aim to put the country on a "
sustained, equitable and job creating" basis and to eradicate
poverty within a decade.
</P>
<P>
Tabling the Union Budget for 2000-01 before the parliament here
on Tuesday, Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha listed a number of
initiatives to achieve the objectives such as doubling the
allocation of food grain to those below poverty line and
rationalizing fertilizer subsidy.
</P>
<P>
He proposed to establish a credible framework for fiscal
discipline, saying rural development would be strengthened besides
modernization of traditional industries like textiles, leather,
agro-processing and creation of more job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The minister laid emphasis on strengthening the potential of
knowledge-based industries such as infotech, biotech and
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to remove infrastructure bottlenecks in power, road,
telecommunications, railways, ports and airways and give high
priority to human resources development to eradicate poverty.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Sinha added, the highest priority would be
given to programs and policies in education, health and other
social services with special emphasis to the poorest and weaker
sections of the society.
</P>
<P>
According to the budget, defense expenditure would be
remarkably increased by 28.2 percent to 585.87 billion rupees (
approximately 13.62 billion U.S. dollars) from 455.87 billion
rupees (about 10.6 billion dollars) in the financial year 1999-
2000.
</P>
<P>
More money would be provided for defense whenever required, the
financial minister told the Lok Sabha, the Lower House of Indian
Parliament, which began its budget session last Friday.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest-ever increase in defense expenditure in any
single year in the country.
</P>
<P>
Sinha said in the budget that fiscal deficit in the last fiscal
year which will end on March 31 was likely to go up to 5.6 percent
of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) from the original target of 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The financial boss proposed that government equity in the
public sector banks be reduced to 33 percent by issuing shares to
the general public and introducing a single rate central value
added tax of 16 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
