<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feb.29 Y2K Crossover Uneventful In Singapore with  OneMinor Glitch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 29 (Xinhua)-- The February 29 Y2K crossover
was generally uneventful in Singapore with one minor glitch, says
a statement released by Singapore's Inforcom Development Authority
(IDA) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary of the Ministry of Communications and
Information Technology Alan Chan, the National Y2K spokesperson,
said in the statement that there were no reports of major
incidents in Singapore arising from the February 29 Y2K critical
date and the crossover in Singapore's five key sectors: finance,
telecommunications, transportation utility and healthcare, has
generally been smooth.
</P>
<P>
IDA said there was one minor incident reported by the Singapore
Mass Rail Transport (SMRT) Limited.
</P>
<P>
The SMRT said the date stamped on 10 single-trip tickets issued
from the SMRT ticket vending machines at the Ochard and City Hall
stations after 1200 midnight was March 1 instead of February 29,
2000.
</P>
<P>
The problem has since been rectified and SMRT will continue to
monitor the situation closely, IDA added.
</P>
<P>
Alan Chan said that "this minor glitch has been quickly
corrected and we are confident that the public will not be further
inconvenienced."
</P>
<P>
He expects no major disruptions would arise on the day and
reassured that Singaporeans can expect to pass the day smoothly
and trouble-free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
