<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Leap Year Computer Problem Reported in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Leap Year's extra day caused
no problem in Thailand's computer systems so far, a senior
official from the country's technology agency told Xinhua Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kwanchai Lamubol, assistance director of the National
Electronics and Computer Technology Center (NECTEC), said that so
far since Monday, NECTEC received no report about any computer
glitches caused by the leap year.
</P>
<P>
February 29, 2000, is considered the last critical date for the
year in which glitches may show up. Some experts voiced concern
that if computers do not recognize the year 2000 as a leap year,
its calendar may get confused, with results similar to those
expected after the transition from 1999 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Kwanchai said that NECTEC reactivated its Y2K command center on
Monday but with only 10 officials on duty compared to 300 on New
Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
The command center opened the whole night on Monday but will
close Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Kwanchai said the center will reopen on Wednesday to collect
reports from 36 organizations to have a whole picture of Thailand'
s Y2K situation.
</P>
<P>
The 36 organizations, including 21 agencies in critical sectors
and 15 ministries, compile information about their computer
systems from subordinate units.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bank of Thailand (BOT) said that it has found no
problem in its credit and payment systems as well as the 88
financial institutions under its control.
</P>
<P>
Napajorn Hemachandra, director of BOT's information technology
group, told Xinhua that the bank's daily operation is "okay."
</P>
<P>
She said that despite the calm day Tuesday, the bank will still
monitor the normal problem which might occur at the transition of
each month.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has met no Y2K problems when the new millennium
arrived. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
