<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Launches Financial Institutions Development Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government
Tuesday formally launched Financial Institutions Development
Project (FIDP) of 52 million U.S. dollars, with 47 million dollars
credit coming from the World Bank (WB).
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the FIDP is to stimulate the financial
market and support the policies of non-banking financial
institutions in a healthy and efficient manner.
</P>
<P>
"The project would undoubtedly be helpful in stimulating the
country's financial market, which is one of the major segments for
investment," said Governor of Bangladesh Bank Dr. Mohammed
Farashuddin.
</P>
<P>
WB Resident Mission Chief Frederick Temple said Bangladesh's
financial system can be characterized as bank-based rather than
market-based.
</P>
<P>
In Bangladesh, the major portion of financing for business and
a majority of the core financial services are provided by banks,
said Mr. Temple, adding that in market-based financial systems,
the major portion of financing and services come from the capital
market.
</P>
<P>
On the launching of FIDP, Temple said the project would
increase the diversity in financial instruments, helping financial
institutions to scrutinize financial assets in order to raise
funds from the market.
</P>
<P>
Financial institutions will also be encouraged and assisted to
issue bonds and other commercial paper as another way of raising
funds from the market, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
