<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Visits Kaduna for Damage Assessment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo has expressed shock over the level of human carnage and
destruction of property in last week's religious clash in the
country's northern Kaduna State.
</P>
<P>
The president was on an assessment tour in Kaduna Metropolis
Monday, accompanied by Acting Governor of the Kaduna State Stephen
Shekari, the Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During his one-day trip, Obasanjo visited many riot sites like
Rigasa, Kabala west, Angwuan Muazu and television village, said
the paper.
</P>
<P>
He expressed dissatisfaction with the attitude of political,
community and religious leaders to the crisis in Kaduna. He,
however, assured that the country will remain indivisible in spite
of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"I feel very sad for what I have seen because I could not
imagine the magnitude of destruction that took place last Monday
and Tuesday," said the president when addressing religious,
traditional and community leaders during the trip.
</P>
<P>
The president urged all leaders -- religious, traditional and
political - - to embark on reconciliation moves at the local and
state levels to heal the wounds the entire community may be
nursing as a result of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"What has happened has destroyed the community because people
who were your neighbors yesterday suddenly turned against you.
Confidence has been shattered. The earlier we work to bring
confidence back the better," said Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
The riot broke out in the city of Kaduna between the Christians
and Moslems who demand for the introduction of Sharia law, killing
at least 400 people. 
</P>
