<HEADLINE> OECD Optimistic About Euro Zone Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) said on Tuesday that the
economic growth rate in the 11 euro zone countries could attain 2.
8 percent in 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
The OECD also called on these countries to speed up their
structural reforms especially in the labor market.
</P>
<P>
In a report on analyzing the results of economic performance by
euro zone countries over the past year, the OECD said it maintains
its prediction that these countries will attain a 2.8 percent
growth in the coming two years.
</P>
<P>
The countries in the euro zone experienced a 2.1-percent growth
of their gross domestic product in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But OECD said that euro zone countries are faced with "major
challenges" in the field of public finance to pay for the social
security of a growing population of retirees and aged people.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the labor market of the euro countries is
still too rigid and should be reformed.
</P>
<P>
The OECD said the euro countries should adopt a policy of "
salary moderation" to limit the labor costs, which it said can
help limit the rising of the interest rate of the European Central
Bank, help create jobs and push forward growth.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it played down the effect of the devaluation of the
euro against the U.S. dollar, saying that compared with the
devaluation of the currencies in Asian countries, the drop of the
euro appears more limited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
