<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "National Ear Care Day" Set in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Starting from this year, March
3 has become "National Ear Care Day" in China.
</P>
<P>
The theme for this year's National Ear Care Day, organized by
the China Disabled Persons Federation and the Ministry of Health,
is "Preventing Deafness Caused by Taking Medicine."
</P>
<P>
China's deaf population has reached 20.57 million, accounting
for one third of the country's total disabled. About 800,000
Chinese children under seven are deaf and 9.49 million elderly
people suffer from deafness.
</P>
<P>
Over 30,000 Chinese children lose their hearing each year due
to medicine taking, hereditary-related problems, diseases and
noise pollution.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Yonggong, a pharmacy expert said that antibacterial is the
"main culprit" responsible for ear nerve problems that can lead to
deafness. Even doctors do not take the necessary precautions to
prevent such "disasters".
</P>
<P>
The number of children under seven suffering from deafness will
be reduced by 10,000 to 20,000 every year, if China can tighten
and control the kinds of medicine that can cause deafness and
educate the populace on how to take the right medicine, according
to Chinese experts.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health issued regulations last year on medicine
that can cause deafness.
</P>
<P>
Deng Pufang, chairman of the Chinese Disabled Persons
Federation, said that China has over 1,500 organizations that
cater for the deaf. Since 1988, nearly 130,000 deaf mute children
have learned to speak. Seventeen percent of them have entered
kindergartens and primary schools.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
