<HEADLINE> HK Aviation Sector Has Smooth Y2K Rollover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's aviation sector
experienced smooth local and Universal Coordinated Time rollovers
to February 29, 2000, without any Y2K-caused computer glitches, a
spokesman for the Civil Aviation Department (CAD) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"All of the Department's air traffic control systems and
equipment such as radars, communications facilities and navigation
equipment have been functioning normally since the rollovers," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said that air traffic operations remain normal and no
computer glitches were reported by the Airport Authority Hong Kong
(AAHK), the Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals Limited, the Hong Kong
based airlines and AAHK's business partners.
</P>
<P>
CAD's Y2K Coordination and Control Center was opened at 10 p.m.
Monday to liaise with the neighboring air traffic control
authorities on the regional rollover status, and to oversee and
monitor the transition to February 29, 2000 , another Y2K critical
date, for the aviation sector of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Between midnight and 8.30 a.m. Tuesday, there were 43 flight
movements, 19 arrivals and 24 departures, at the Hong Kong
International Airport (HKIA). A total of 467 scheduled flight
movements are expected at HKIA Tuesday, being the same as the
usual daily traffic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
