<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Has Smooth Rollover to February 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Essential services in Hong
Kong have continued to function smoothly following the region's
smooth rollover to February 29, 2000 without any Y2K-induced
computer glitches, a Hong Kong official announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Jessie Ting, deputy secretary for Information Technology and
Broadcasting and the controller of the government's Y2K Central
Coordinating Center (CCC), said Hong Kong had entered February 29,
2000 without any disruptions in the provision of critical public
services.
</P>
<P>
"The CCC will continue to closely monitor the territory-wide
rollover situation through regular reports from the 13 sector-wide
coordinating centers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 13 essential service sectors are aviation, broadcasting,
energy supply, environment, fire and emergency services, financial
services, food supply, border control, port management, public
health, public order, telecommunications and transport.
</P>
<P>
Ting said that both the government and essential services
providers had put in place comprehensive contingency arrangements
to ensure a prompt response to any unforeseen Y2K-induced system
failures.
</P>
<P>
"With these well-tested contingency arrangements, the risk that
Hong Kong will be adversely affected by the Y2K problem during the
rollover to February 29 is minimal," she said.
</P>
<P>
Small and medium-sized businesses experiencing Y2K-related
problems with their computers, which fail to recognize 2000 as a
leap year, can contact the Hong Kong Productivity Council for
assistance. The Council is operating a 24-hour hotline to answer
inquiries on Y2K-related matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
