<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Official Visits Georgia to Discuss Pipeline Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Hikmet Cetin, Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel's advisor and former foreign minister and deputy
prime minister, has paid a visit to Georgia for the implementation
of the Baku-Ceyhan pipeline project.
</P>
<P>
Cetin said he delivered a message from Demirel to Georgian
President Eduard Shevardnadze, urging him to accelerate the
negotiation process with Azerbaijan, Turkish Daily News reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is anxious to implement the oil pipeline project
agreement, reached among the three countries on the sidelines of
last November's summit of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation jin Europe, which was held in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline will transport crude oil across Georgia from Baku
of Azerbaijan to the Turkish port of Ceyhan.
</P>
<P>
Georgia is reportedly attempting to gain a higher tariff - 0.20
U.S. dollars per barrel - for the transport of oil through its
territory and has also insisted that it will not assume any
responsibility for the security of its section of the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, however, in a move intended to urge Georgia into
complying, has offered assistance to Georgia in the form of
military training, equipment, electronic surveillance systems and
ammunition to help maintain security of the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Cetin said he believed Shevardenadze is determined to carry out
the project, but it is understood that Georgia will wait for the
outcome of the April 9 presidential elections before making a final
decision on the negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
