<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6,500 Italian Women Apply For Air Force Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Some 6,500 Italian women begin
competing Monday for posts in the national air force marking a new
page in the history of the Italian Armed Forces, whose ranks have
always been closed to female recruits.
</P>
<P>
A total of 136 jobs are up for grabs in the Italian air force
of which 28 are, for the first time ever, earmarked for women,
including 16 posts as pilots.
</P>
<P>
In all, 13,000 people have applied for the jobs, half of them
women. The preliminary selection procedures started Monday and
will last until March 3.
</P>
<P>
Female candidates are required to have Italian citizenship, if
they are aged between 17 and 25 and have a high school diploma.
They must also be unmarried, without children and at least 1.61
meters tall, or 1.65 meters if they wish to become pilots or
navigators.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a group of male recruits protested today against
military academy regulations that permit female recruits who marry
and have children to complete their training while throwing out
males automatically for such actions.
</P>
<P>
Last September, the Italian government decided to let women
join the forces. It also abolished compulsory military service and
put Italy's armed forces on a totally voluntary and professional
footing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
