</P>
<P>
-- Ministers and Knesset (parliament) members from three ruling
coalition partners met Monday night in advance of Wednesday's
Knesset vote on Likud's bill that would require an absolute
majority in a national referendum plus 61 legislators' favorable
votes to endorse any treaty the government signs with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Shas, the National Religious Party and Yisrael Ba'aliya had
threatened to vote for the opposition Likud party and against the
government on the bill, which was perceived as an effort to
neutralize the Israeli Arabs' vote.
</P>
<P>
The government worries that if the bill passes, it would mean a
coalition crisis.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
