<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Economists Optimistic Over Economic  Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian economists voiced
their optimistic about the country's economy, saying the
government's economic growth target of 4 percent or more this year
could be reached.
</P>
<P>
Anggito Abimanyu, a noted economist of the Gadjah Mada
University, told Xinhua on Tuesday that the government could reach
the target of its economic growth (4 percent) easily if security
and political situation in Indonesia is conducive enough for
investment.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the country's economic growth will be
influenced by the growth in some neighboring countries such as
Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Asia Pacific Director of the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) Yazuke Horiguchi also said that Indonesia's economy
this year would reach 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia's economic growth has shown progress," Horiguchi,
who just replaced Hurbert Neiss, said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a memorandum of economic and financial policies
signed by the IMF and the government of Indonesia issued on
January 20, Indonesia's economy is predicted to grow by 1- 2
percent in 1999/2000 fiscal year ending on March 31, 2000, and
then to strengthen to the 3-4 percent during the fiscal year of
2000 (April-December).
</P>
<P>
Abimanyu noted that the target of 4 percent is a conservative
figure, saying that actually the government could reach more than
4 percent in the fiscal year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Meantime, in an attempt to make the 2000 state budget strong to
boost the on-going economic recovery program, the Advisory Group
in Economic, Industry, and Trade (Econit), one of the noted
country's economic think-tank, urged on Tuesday the government to
revise its draft of the country's 2000 state budget.
</P>
<P>
In its public policy review journal issued on Tuesday, the
Group said that the government needs to make its fiscal policy
more expansive.
</P>
<P>
The government was also urged to carry on foreign debt
rescheduling.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia, so far has behaved as a good boy in the payment of
its foreign debt, so we think we are deserve to ask for debt
reduction. It is important for Indonesia to reduce its foreign
debt stock," Econit Director Arif Arryman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
