<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Build 10 More Industrial Institutes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia plans to build
10 more industrial training institutes (ITI) under its 8th Five
Year Plan (2001-2005), Human Resources Minister Fong Chan Onn said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move, which would cost around 1.3 billion ringgit (342.105
million U.S. dollars), is to ensure sufficient supply of skilled
manpower in the industrial sector in the country, he told
reporters here after addressing the one-day conference on "
Education as an Engine for Growth and Innovation in a Knowledge
Economy".
</P>
<P>
Under the 7th Malaysia Plan, Malaysia has 10 ITIs which are
being upgraded, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Once we complete the upgrading works by the end of this year,
we expect the next intake for ITIs to increase to 17,000 students,
compared with 4,300 trainees now," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that with the new ITIs, his ministry intended
to work on specialization in certain skills to ensure optimal and
efficient utilization of available resources.
</P>
<P>
He said a total of 23,900 trainees were produced by the all
public training institutions annually.
</P>
<P>
Fong said that the government has allocated 500 million ringgit
(131.578 million U.S. dollars) under the Skills Training Loan Fund
to help students from the lower income group. 
</P>
