<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayon Resumes Blasts, Ash Fall Triggers Blackout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- A series of blasts rocked Mayon
at noon Tuesday, sending volume of ash under the heavy rains that
fell in big muddy drops in Albay province, grounding power cables
and insulators and plunging the province in total blackout.
</P>
<P>
The noon day blasts occurring at 12:11 p.m. and 12:20 p.m. were
stronger than Monday's explosions, according to Ted Sandoval, an
expert of Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (
Phivolcs) Lignon Hills Observatory in Legazpi City.
</P>
<P>
Sandoval said in a report that Monday's and Tuesday's
explosions were stronger than Mayon's 1968, 1984 and 1993 blasts.
</P>
<P>
He said rain clouds covering the volcano's peak rendered visual
observation hard, hiding the rather huge eruptions column.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains pelted Albay at noon while the eruption was taking
place and disaster experts issued warnings of possible lahar
avalanches.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Albay Electric Cooperative said muds-mixture
of ash rains covered and grounded power insulators forcing them to
shut down electricity in the entire province.
</P>
<P>
The Philvolcs maintains Alert Level 5 of the country's most
active volcano "since there is still high potential for
occurrences of pyroclastic flows."
</P>
<P>
The institute said strict compliance of the 6-kilometer radius
permanent danger zone and the extension to 8-kilometer in the
southeast sector should be observed.
</P>
<P>
Mayon Volcano erupted last Thursday, sending lava fountains and
huge columns of smoke to the sky as thousands of local residents
fled their homes to evacuation centers.
</P>
<P>
Located about 300 kilometers southeast of Manila, the 2,462-
meter Mayon Volcano has erupted at least 40 times since 1616 and
its last major eruption was in 1993, which killed at least 77
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
