<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Urges Nigeria to Step up Anti-corruption Crusade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Commonwealth Secretary General
Emeka Anyaoku said Monday that the Nigerian government needed
"progress" in its battle against corruption before it could expect
to attract foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
"Potential investors would like to see progress being made in
tackling corruption before agreeing to finance investment in
Nigeria," he said at the opening of a three-day
Commonwealth-Nigeria Investment Conference in Abuja, the capital
of Africa's most populous country.
</P>
<P>
The Nigeria-born secretary general also identified the
recurring religious and ethnic clash, and inefficiency of the
public service as " inimical" to foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The problem relating to Sharia must be given great attention,
Anyaoku told entrepreneurs, bankers, and economists attending the
conference jointly organized by the Nigerian government and the
Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
Lack of progress in rescheduling Nigeria's 29 billion U.S.
dollar debt would undermine the ongoing process of "political and
economic reform", warned Anyaoku.
</P>
<P>
