<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's War Veterans Pour Into White-owned Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's former freedom
fighters launched a countrywide invasion of white-owned commercial
farms to push for equitable redistribution of land, the daily
Herald reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
By Monday night the veterans had invaded at least 12 farms
countrywide in the past two weeks, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The ex-combatants Monday continued to pour into commercial
farms in different parts of the country, saying the time had come
to take "part of our heritage, which was illegally taken away
from our forefathers".
</P>
<P>
The invasions started in the southern Masvingo Province and
have now spread to virtually all the country's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
About 700 former freedom fighters Monday descended on Muzuri
Farms in Ruwa, just outside Harare.
</P>
<P>
Asked what the police were doing about the invasions, Police
Commissioner Augustine Chihuri said the issue was "above the
police" because it was political and referred the reporters to
politicians.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Vice-President Joseph Msika, who is also chairman of
the National Land Acquisition Committee, said on Monday night the
government would only take a position after the local leadership
in the provinces had briefed it on the invasion. 
</P>
