<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mysterious Disease Threatens Flamingos in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 29 (Xinhua) -- A mysterious disease is
killing tens of thousands of flamingos on Lake Bogoria in Rift
Valley Province, central Kenya, the East African Standard reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted conservationists as saying human pollution is
the cause of the disease which has since last July killed up to
50,000 birds on the lake.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the world's flamingo population live on the
eastern Rift Valley lakes, with vast majority living on the
30-square-kilometers Lake Bogoria, the real haven left for the
bird in the country.
</P>
<P>
"In every single bird which we collected and analyzed tissues,
we found up to nine or 10 heavy metals," said Gideon Motelin who
specializes in flamingo studies at Kenya's Egerton University.
</P>
<P>
"It is not normal to find arsenic, lead, mercury, chromium and
copper in the livers and kidneys of these birds," he said, adding
that traces of pesticide have also been found in the body tissue
of the dead birds.
</P>
<P>
Conservationists believe that the source of pollution is the
farms near Lake Nakuru, about 100 kilometers south of Bogoria.
Flamingos abandoned Lake Nakuru two years ago due to pollution as
the lake became virtually uninhabitable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda, Sudan to Resume Talks in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and the Sudan will
resume ministerial talks on the implementation of the peace
agreement signed by the two countries' presidents last December.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Minister for Presidency Ruhakana Rugunda told Xinhua on
Tuesday that the talks would start on Wednesday in the Kenyan
capital Nairobi and last through to the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"We would discuss what major progress we have achieved so far
in the implementation of the agreement and what should be done
next," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement, brokered by former U.S. President Jimmy
Carter, committed the two countries to ending hostility and
returning prisoners of war or people abducted by rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to restore full diplomatic relations by the end of
February if the commitment was fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
On several occasions, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
expressed his dissatisfaction with the lag of its implementation,
saying that the Sudanese government did not honor its promise of
returning all the children abducted by the rebel Lord's Resistance
Army in northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and the Sudan have been accusing each other of backing
rebel activities on their respective land and cut diplomatic
relations in April 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
