<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Success in Breeding Panda Cubs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Artificial panda-breeding
techniques have been hailed as a success in China with the
survival of all five giant panda cubs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, prior to 1998, only 30 percent of baby
pandas could be bred through artificial breeding at the Chengdu
Giant Panda Breeding Research Center in southwest China's Sichuan
Wolong Natural Reserve.
</P>
<P>
Of the five baby pandas, one was born in 1998 and the other
four in 1999. They are all reported to be in good condition.
</P>
<P>
The Chengdu Giant Panda Breeding Research Center, China's most
professional panda research institution, is fully confident that
in the future they will have a hundred per cent survival rate of
artificially-bred baby pandas.
</P>
<P>
Giant panda only conceive one or two babies each year. Many
newborn cubs are often abandoned by their mothers because they
cannot feed or take care of two cubs at once.
</P>
<P>
The research center initiated a program from 1991-1997 to save
baby pandas by artificial breeding. However, in the early stages
of the program, six panda cubs died.
</P>
<P>
The death of some of the baby pandas was due to mixing
different milk ingredients, said Zhang Guiquan, assistant director
with the center.
</P>
<P>
After tests and experiments, experts changed the milk for
feeding panda cubs in 1998 which proved successful in the survival
of all five cubs.
</P>
<P>
Staff at the Panda Research Center look after newly-born pandas
during the first 11 days of birth, considered to be the most
critical period. Young pandas will then be removed from a special
caring room to a simulated wild environment to become familiar
with their new surroundings, said Zhang Hemin, director of the
research center.
</P>
<P>
China is making a blueprint to release pandas from captivity by
2005 after they receive training exercises in their simulated
environment.
</P>
<P>
Some mature female pandas are watching videos of other mother
pandas raising their offspring at the research center. Recorded
sounds of little pandas are also broadcasted regularly to arouse "
motherhood" in these female pandas.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is on the verge of extinction. There are about
1,000 pandas in the world, most of which live in China. About 100
pandas are bred by artificial insemination or through artificial
breeding programs.
</P>
<P>
China has set up 27 natural reserves to protect pandas and is
building another 17 areas to breed and raise pandas.
</P>
<P>
Among all panda protecting reserves in China, the Wolong
natural reserve is the largest with over 100 wild giant pandas.
About 50 of these pandas are in captivity.
</P>
<P>
The Chengdu Giant Panda Breeding Research Center was founded in
1980, 100 kilometers away from the capital of Chengdu. The Center
was sponsored by the Chinese government and World Wild Fund For
Nature. The Reserve covers a total area of over 30 hectares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
