<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China's Entry Into WTO Accelerated (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- China's entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO) has been much accelerated over the past
several months as the country signed WTO deals with a dozen member
of the multi-lateral trade body.
</P>
<P>
Following the China-US agreement concerning China's entry into
the WTO last November, China has since signed bilateral WTO
agreements with Canada, Cuba, Venezuela, Brazil, Sri Lanka,
Uruguay, Peru, Norway, Iceland, the Philippines and India.
</P>
<P>
China has yet to reach agreement with another 13 WTO members --
the EU, Argentina, Columbia, Costa Rica, Guatemala, Girghizstan,
Latvia, Malaysia, Mexico, Poland, Switzerland and Thailand --
before it finally becomes WTO member.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC) said that negotiations with the above 13
members are all under way.
</P>
<P>
China's bid to enter the WTO has lasted 14 years. Before the
China-US WTO deal was clinched, there was little progress.
</P>
<P>
Between 1986 and 1999, China held numerous negotiations with
the United States and other major WTO members on its accession to
the WTO, previously known as the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade (GATT).
</P>
<P>
During this period, China almost reached a deal with the United
States, but failed because of the U.S's unrealistic high demands
and domestic political factors, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Observers in China said that the acceleration of China's entry
into the WTO came about due to strategic decision by the Chinese
Government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China's Entry Into WTO Accelerated (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"As the People's Daily said recently in a signed article, that
to join the WTO as early as possible by quickening negotiations is
imperative in developing China's socialist market economy as well
as for China to open its doors even wider to the outside world,"
said an analyst, who prefers not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
The "win-win" deal between China and the United States is of
significant and far-reaching importance, said the analyst.
</P>
<P>
As the largest developed country in the world, the United
States is a major player in global trade and economy. The United
States greatly influences world trade and the rules which govern
global trade.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-US agreement has cleared the biggest obstacle for
China's entry into the WTO, paving the way for a quicker process
of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Following the Sino-US agreement, many WTO members, including
the EU, have said they would accelerate negotiations with China to
enable the country to join the WTO at the earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
It is generally agreed upon that China's WTO membership will be
good for China and global trade.
</P>
<P>
Mike Moore, WTO director-general, said during his recent visit
to Beijing that WTO will only truly be a world trade organization
until China becomes a member, adding that the day China enters the
WTO will be a great day for China and the world.
</P>
<P>
China is now making preparations for that historical day.
Major newspapers, including the "People's Daily", "Economic Daily"
and the "Guangming Daily", have run a series of articles about the
WTO.
</P>
<P>
According to MOFTEC Minister Shi Guangsheng, China is making
amendments that accord with WTO regulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Allegations on HK Human Rights Situation Unjustified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- It is entirely unjustified for
the U.S. State Department to make allegations, regardless of the
fact, about human rights situation in Hong Kong in its human
rights report, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said
here today.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on the U.S. report, Zhu said that it has
met with criticism from the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) government and people from all walks of life in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The central government of China and HKSAR government have been
following the principles of "one country, two systems," "Hong Kong
people administering the affairs of Hong Kong" and a high degree
of autonomy since the return of Hong Kong, he said, adding that
people there continue to enjoy a wide range of human rights,
democracy and freedom as safeguarded by the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
"This is a fact generally recognized by the international
community and it is most inappropriate for the U.S. to make
uninvited remarks on and unwarranted interference in Hong Kong's
internal affairs," Zhu noted.
</P>
<P>
"We express our firm opposition to that," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
