<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Ready to Help East Timor: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President
Abdurrahman Wahid Tuesday reaffirmed the country's readiness to
help East Timor build its future, saying both countries had once
been occupied by colonizers.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after arriving at the Comorro Airport in Dili, capital
of East Timor, the president said: "We will give whatever we can
give."
</P>
<P>
The president arrived in Dili on Tuesday morning for a one-day
visit. It is the first visit of an Indonesian head of state after
East Timor separated from Indonesia following a ballot organized
by the United Nations on August 30 last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Antara News Agency, Wahid was met by East
Timorese Independence leader Xanana Gusmao, Chief of the U.N.
Transitional Administration in East Timor (UNTAET) Sergio de Mello,
Nobel laureate Jose Ramos Horta and Dili Bishop Carlos Filipe
Ximenes Belo.
</P>
<P>
"Long live Pak Gus Dur (Mr. Wahid)! Long live Indonesia! Long
live the East Timorese!" Xanana cried.
</P>
<P>
The president was accompanied by acting Coordinating Minister
for Political and Security Affairs Surjadi Soedirdja, Coordinating
Minister for the People's Welfare Basri Hasanuddin, Foreign
Minister Alwi Shihab, Attorney General Marzuki Darusman and chief
of the Indonesian Defense Force Adm. Widodo A.S.
</P>
<P>
During his short visit, Wahid is scheduled to hold a series of
talks with East Timorese leaders and the UNTAET chief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
