<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine GNP Expected to Grow 4.5 Pct This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government's
economic managers foresee generally sunny weather for this year,
placing Gross National Product (GNP) at 4.5 percent from last year
's 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
During a recently concluded workshop on Regional Development,
Director General Felipe Medalla of the National Economic and
Development Authority said the country's Gross Domestic Product (
GDP) will increase by 4 percent or higher in 2000.
</P>
<P>
"GDP plus overseas remittances, we could do as well as 4.5
percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Medalla's rosy projections was shared by 116 business leaders
from Northern Luzon, Southern Luzon and Metro Manila who, in a
flash survey, indicated optimism this year's economic growth will
be higher than 1999's.
</P>
<P>
About 59 percent of the respondents believe GNP growth in 2000
will be better than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Majority of the business leaders cited addressing
infrastructure bottlenecks and efforts at fiscal discipline and
better management of the budget to enable the government to meet
fiscal targets to be the primary concern of the government this
year.
</P>
<P>
They also believe economic growth will also be boosted by the
government's proposed economic legislation aimed at improving the
business climate.
</P>
<P>
The business leaders said the country's increasing trade
surplus, single-digit interest rates and low inflation rate will
also contribute to the faster economic growth in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
