<HEADLINE> PLA Chief of Staff Meets U.S. Pacific Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Fu Quanyou, Chief of General
Staff of the People's Liberation Army (PLA) of China, warned
today that the U.S. government should not let the Sino-U.S.
relations and bilateral military ties which have shown a trend of
resumption and improvement suffer from setbacks once again.
</P>
<P>
Fu made the remarks when meeting with Dennis Blair, commander-
in-chief of pacific command of the United States armed forces in
the newly-launched "August 1st" building, the headquarters of the
Central Military Commission (CMC).
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the U.S. government will proceed from the
strategic height of maintaining regional peace and stability, take
decisively effective measures to prevent the Congress from passing
the Taiwan Security Enhancement Act," Fu said.
</P>
<P>
Fu, also a CMC member, said that the Sino-U.S. relations is
right now at an important period which faces both opportunities
for improvement and development, and problems calling for urgent
handling, and the Taiwan issue is a key one.
</P>
<P>
Fu said he was happy to meet Blair and his group, as the
delegation he is leading marks the resumption of senior military
exchange and bilateral army relations onto the normal rack.
</P>
<P>
Blair agreed that his visit is a major step in resuming the
army to army relations. He reiterated his government's stance of
sticking to the "One-china" policy. 
