<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Ambassador to China Stresses China's WTO Accession, PNTR Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
WASHINGTON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to China,
Joseph W. Prueher, said here Monday that China's World Trade
Organization (WTO) accession and permanent normal trade status
with the U.S. are on the top of the U.S. government agenda in
handling its relations with China this year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a policy briefing sponsored by the National
Committee of United States-China Relationship, Prueher also said
the United States should support the economic reform and rule of
law in China, and put forward human rights dialogue and military-
to-military contact between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
China's accession to the WTO, "the number one issue on the
list," will serve America's political, economic and military
interests in the long run, Prueher told a group of China experts
at the briefing.
</P>
<P>
"So we need not take our eyes off the ball," said the 58-year-
old Admiral-turned-diplomat who just came back home after three
months in China.
</P>
<P>
"We should support (China's) WTO accession" and grant it
Permanent Normal Trade Relations (PNTR), because this will help
the reforms in China, Prueher noted, calling on the Americans to "
do everything" to buttress China's reform in such fields as
economic restructuring, banking, financing, so that America's
business firms may enjoy a good deal of fairness in competition on
China's market.
</P>
<P>
Prueher also stressed the need to support the development of
rule of law in China, saying that the Chinese people are working
hard toward establishing a legal society in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador also urged support for continued human rights
dialogue with China, but cautioned that when conducting the
dialogue, the United States should take into account what China
has achieved in improving its human rights in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
"We should acknowledge what has been done (in China) over the
last 20 years, which is in a considerable amount," he said.
</P>
<P>
In China, he added, many people who starved in the past are
now having enough to eat, and there are more nongovernmental
organizations and greater individual freedom than before, and
there are also a larger number of churches in China, where worship
is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Prueher expressed his opposition to the Taiwan Security
Enhancement Act, saying the Act will worsen the situation in the
Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives passed the Act last month
despite China's strong opposition. China says that the Act will
pose a severe threat to China's security and increase the chances
of military confrontation across the straits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
