<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4th Race of America's Cup Finals to Be Sailed on Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 29 (Xinhua) -- With four race days lost
and only three races sailed, the Race Committee of the America's
Cup have just decided to change its schedule and the fourth race
of the America's Cup finals series will now be sailed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There was never a hint of wind on Tuesday on the Hauraki Gulf
off Auckland, the largest city of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
A sunny morning gave way to a hazy, cloudy afternoon and didn't
generate enough heat to build a sea breeze. The wind velocity
never exceeded four knots before Race Director Harold Bennett
abandoned racing at 14:45 (local time).
</P>
<P>
But according to weather forecasts, tropical rain storms will
move into the area from the North over Wednesday afternoon,
resulting in Northeasterly winds of 10-15 tomorrow building to 20-
25 knot Easterlies on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Based on the forecasts, the Race Committee has just changed its
schedule and decided the 4th race will be held on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There have now been four postponements in the 11 days since the
America's Cup finals began, meaning the series is set to be the
longest-ever in the event's 149-year history.
</P>
<P>
Defender Team New Zealand holds a three-nil lead over
challenger Prada.  
</P>
</TEXT>
