<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Has Most Nature Reserves in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Yunnan Province in southwest
China now has 105 nature reserves, ranking first in the country.
</P>
<P>
The reserves established over the past four decades, cover an
area of 1.95 million hectares, or 5 percent of the province's
territory. They had served as shelters to protect 100 kinds of
forests and 90 percent of the province's rare species of
endangered animals and plants, according to Chen Jihai, director
of the provincial forestry department.
</P>
<P>
As the most biodiverse region in China, Yunnan, with only one
25th of the national territory, is home to 17,000 kinds of high-
grade plants, or half of the country's total. And half of the
country's wild animal species could also be located in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, Yunnan, known as China's "kingdom of
animals and plants", has issued a series of rules and regulations
to protect its biodiversity and crack down on illegal poaching of
wild animals.
</P>
<P>
In 1999 alone, forest police handled over 10,000 cases related
to poaching wild animals and destroying forest resources. And 16,
000 people were dealt with according to law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many international organizations, such as the World
Wildlife Fund (WWF), the International Union for the Conservation
of Nature (IUCN), the Food and Agricultural Organization and
UNESCO, have also conducted cooperative projects with Yunnan to
protect the province's biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
Local residents' initiative to protect biological resources has
also been enhanced. In 1995, an association aimed at protecting
biological resources was sponsored by farmers living in the
Gaoligongshan nature reserve, which was set up in 1981.
</P>
<P>
"It's our duty to protect natural environment," said Li Jiahu,
an official of the association, adding that "we could no longer
live here once ecological environment was being damaged."
</P>
<P>
Due to the effort, local forestry department said, Asian
elephants in the jungles of Xishuangbanna in southern Yunnan have
increased from 150 in the 1970s to about 300 at present, the
number of Yunnan golden monkey in the Weixisamage nature reserve
has tripled from about 200 to over 600, and black gibbon in the
Wuliangshan nature reserve has increased from 150 to more than 400.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,000-Year-Old Tea Trees Still Productive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Patches of ancient tea
plantation, believed to be more than 1,000 year old, in southwest
China's Yunnan Province, are still producing teas, and bringing
benefit for local people.
</P>
<P>
The tea trees in one patch, each three to four meters high on
average and 1.6 meters in diameter, cover an area of about 600
hectares in the mountainous areas in the Lahu Autonomous County of
Lancang, southern Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
Inscriptions on a monument in Dai language reads that the trees
were planted in the year of 696.
</P>
<P>
From March to November every year, local people can collect tea
four to five times from the trees, said Yan Shanyong, head of the
Jingmai Village.
</P>
<P>
The tea from the trees tastes quite different from normal tea
plantations, Yan said, adding that it is environmentally friendly
as neither chemical fertilizer nor pesticides were used for them.
</P>
<P>
The tea was also sold at a much higher price compared with
ordinary tea. However, the average per ha output of the ancient
trees was low , only 300 kg per hectare.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the tea plantations have become a tourism attraction
over the past few years, and this has also brought about benefit
for local people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
