<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Striving to Boost Tourism Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 29 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province announced that it has extended its visa-free tour program
from covering only two cities of Shenzhen and Zhuhai to nine
cities in the Pearl River Delta.
</P>
<P>
The program is applicable to overseas tourists with visas to
visit Hong Kong and Macao. Under the program, they will be allowed
to stay five more days when visiting the nine cities in the Pearl
River Delta without having to obtain extra visas after they
finished tours in Hong Kong or Macao, said Lu Weixiong, head of
Guangdong Provincial Tourism Administration.
</P>
<P>
Previously, overseas tourists with visas to travel to Hong Kong
and Macao were given a 72-hour visa treatment and allowed to visit
Shenzhen and Zhuhai in Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
According to Lu, the new visa-free extension plan is designed
to attract more tourists to Guangdong from both Hong Kong and
Macao. The plan has won approval by the relevant central
departments.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that he believed Disney Company's decision to select
Hong Kong as the venue of its new theme park was made based on the
confidence in investment environment in the greater triangle
formed by Guangdong, Hong Kong and Macao and in China's continued
open-up policy.
</P>
<P>
Lu added that a closer cooperation among people from tourism
communities of Hong Kong, Guangdong and Macao is a necessity to
achieve success of implementing the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
