<HEADLINE> Scientists Urged to Push Forward Reform of State-owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- A symposium was held in
Beijing today to encourage scientists and technologists to push
forward reforms of state-owned enterprises and accelerate economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The two-day symposium was hosted by the China Association for
Science and Technology. Zhang Yutai, vice president of Association
said at the meeting that the technological expertise in state-
owned enterprises lags far behind the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
A survey on 24,000 large and medium-sized Chinese enterprises
shows that only 46.6 percent have their own research departments.
Technological level of industries such as non-ferrous metals,
petrochemicals and electric power lag five to ten years behind the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, there was 48 billion yuan (about 5.78 billion US
dollars) of research and development funds in China's large and
medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Zhang called on science and technology associations to offer
their advice on reforming state-owned enterprises, promote and
develop academic exchanges and raise the scientific and technical
level of workers in state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
