<HEADLINE> U.S. Continues Monitoring Austria Despite Haider's Resignation -- With Correction of Haider's Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Monday that it will continue to monitor the coalition government
of Austria despite the resignation of Joerg Haider as the
chairman of the far-right Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin told a regular
briefing that Haider's resignation would be "a step in the right
direction," but noting that Haider is "still part of the party."
</P>
<P>
Reports from Austria said that Haider would remain governor of
Carinthia and play a role similar to that of a corporate "
supervisory board" in the party after his resignation as the
chairman.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. recalled its ambassador to Austria to protest the
Freedom Party's entrance into the coalition government early this
month. Haider is well known for remarks playing down Nazi crimes
and was strongly criticized in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The other 14 members of the European Union (EU) froze bilateral
political contacts with Austria, also an EU member, to protest
against the joining of the Freedom Party in the new government.
</P>
<P>
In its new policy platform, the Austrian government promised to
reject racism, xenophobia and anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the U.S. will continue to watch the behavior of the
Austrian government to ensure it will keep its promise.
</P>
<P>
"Our focus is going to be on to what extent the government will
live up to the platform it has set forth. So we will be watching
their behavior," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
"This doesn't change our concerns. The Freedom Party is still
part of the government," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
