<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't to Raise Fuel Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government and
the House of Representatives (DPR) state budget committee agreed
to raise fuel prices by an average of 12 percent from the
beginning of April, the Jakarta Post daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The price of premium gasoline would be raised 15 percent to 1,
150 rupiah (about 0.16 U.S. dollars) per liter from the current
price of 1,000 rupiah (0.137 dollars) per liter, the daily quoted
Minister of Mines and Energy Soesilo Bambang Yudhoyono as saying.
</P>
<P>
"But the price of kerosene for the poor and fuel for the public
transportation and (state electricity firm) PLN will not increase,
" the minister said, adding the price of automotive diesel will
increase to 600 rupiah (0.082 dollars) per liter from 550 rupiah (
0.075 dollars) per liter, industrial diesel will increase to 550
rupiah (0.075 dollars) from 500 rupiah (0.068 dollars), kerosene
to 350 rupiah (0.048 dollars) from 280 rupiah (0.03 dollars) and
bunker oil to 400 rupiah (0.055 dollars) per liter from 350 rupiah
(0.048 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Yudhoyono said that the average 12 percent increase in fuel
prices would reduce the government's fuel subsidy in the April-
December 2000 state budget.
</P>
<P>
In its earlier state budget draft, the government proposed a 20
percent increase in fuel prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Faces No Y2K Leap-Year Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Tuesday
completed the rollover into the leap year 2000 without any reports
of systems disruption by the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
"As at 12:30 this morning the National Operations Center has
not received any report of Y2K-related disruptions in the country,
" National Y2K Project Director Nuraizah Abdul Hamid said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The National Operations Center, which activated late Monday to
monitor the situation on a 24-hour basis, would continue to
operate around the clock until 3 p.m. Tuesday, she said.
</P>
<P>
The center also did not anticipate any Y2K-disruptions after
March 1 as all systems and contingency plans were in place, she
said, expressing confidence that all critical-sector operations
would continue smoothly throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, along with governments around the world, made
extensive preparations to ensure high level of Y2K-compliance in
the critical sectors, she said, adding as a result, it enjoyed a
trouble-free New Year on January 1.
</P>
<P>
There was general anxiety over the possibility of the
millennium bug striking on February 29 as some computers may not
be able to recognize 2000 as a leap year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
