<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Playing Key Role in New Zealand Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 29 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand is attracting
more international visitors, who are spending more money than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
Figures released Tuesday by Tourism New Zealand showed that
international visitors spent almost four billion NZ dollars (about
2 billion U.S. dollars) in New Zealand in 1999, registering an
increase of 22 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
George Hickton, chief executive of Tourism New Zealand, said
record figures, coupled with an increase in visitor arrivals of
eight percent during the same period, show that tourism is
increasingly playing a key role in the New Zealand economy.
</P>
<P>
The average daily spend of the international visitors has
increased by 18.5 percent since the end of 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Australia is still New Zealand's largest market both in terms
of numbers visiting and dollars spent, with 523,428 Australian
visitors spending an average of 142 NZ dollars (71 U.S. dollars)
per day. This is an increase spend of eight percent from the year
before, according to Tourism New Zealand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
