<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Marine Fish Output Increases in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's marine fish output
reached 279,900 metric tons in 1999, a 7.6 percent growth over the
previous year, the Ministry of Fisheries and Aquatic Resources
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry in a statement attributed the output increase to
the various incentive packages offered to fishermen.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka, an island nation in the northern Indian Ocean,
possesses 1,200 kilometers' coastline with vast aquatic resources.
About 100,000 Sri Lankans are engaged in fishing activities.
</P>
<P>
The statement said a shift to deep sea fishing had been
encouraged through structural and management reforms. Consequently
over 1,700 boats operate in the country's exclusive economic zone
and in the international waters.
</P>
<P>
Deep sea fishing had also been encouraged by the government by
providing fully equipped harbors and anchorages along the coast.
</P>
<P>
During the past few years three new harbors had been
constructed while existing harbors were provided with essential
facilities for faster turnaround. Financial packages have also
been secured for the construction of an additional five harbors.
</P>
<P>
For more efficient operations and security for deep sea crew
members, the government has provided the fleet with radio
communication sets and satellite navigation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile there has been a decrease in the import of fish and
fishery products from 71,200 metric tons in 1998 to 65,500 metric
tons in 1999, the statement added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
