<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-Lanka Trade Pact Boosts Sri Lankan Tea Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan tea industry
expects a boost from the Indo-Lanka Free Trade Agreement (FTA)
which will take effect next month, the official Daily News Tuesday
quoted a senior industry official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The FTA will certainly be instrumental in boosting the Colombo
tea auction," Chairman of the Colombo Tea Traders' Association
Michael de Zoysa told the paper.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, India agrees to import 15 million kgs of
Sri Lankan tea annually with 50 percent tariff concessions. For
this year there will be a total exportable quantity of 11.5
million kgs for Sri Lankan tea exporters.
</P>
<P>
India is the single largest tea market in the world which
consumes 600 million kgs of tea. Sri Lanka tea exporters have long
been expecting to carve a niche in the Indian tea market.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka and India entered into a free trade agreement when
President C. B. Kumaratunga visited New Delhi in late December
1998.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the pact was delayed for one year due to
differences on whether tea and other items should be enlisted for
tariff concessions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
