<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Gov't Vests More Power to Capital Market Watchdog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
finally vested more regulatory power to the Securities and
Exchange Commission (SEC) to exercise its authority to help
revitalize the country's ailing capital market, The Bangladesh
Observer reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet at a regular meeting Monday approved the draft
amendments to the rules and regulations of the SEC, giving more
power to the country's capital market watchdog.
</P>
<P>
The SEC, established in 1993, was endowed with limited power to
exercise its authority to maintain transparency in the capital
market. Under the previous rules and regulation, the SEC was
unable to check the irregularities in the stock market, which
caused colossal loss to the share investors.
</P>
<P>
The amendments would empower the SEC to take tough action
against the respective person or institution involved in any
misdeal in share trading. The commission could also impose high
penalty on the default-listed companies for their failure to hold
annual general meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
