<HEADLINE> MTA Armed Group Members Surrender to Myanmar Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Senventy-four remnant members
of the Mong Tai Army (MTA), a former drug trafficking armed group
operating in Myanmar's Shan state, surrendered to the government
earlier this month, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The MTA members, who "exchanged arms for peace" with the
government forces in the area of Triangle Region Command on
February 22, was led by U Shaung Yin.
</P>
<P>
They brought with them some arms and ammunition, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
During the last two months, 72 members of the anti-government
Shan-State United Revolutionary Army and 17 members of the Lahu
ethnic armed group operating in the state also surrendered to the
government, according to earlier official reports.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, a total of 17 anti-government ethnic armed groups as
well as the MTA, led by former drug warlord Khun Sa, have reached
cease-fire agreements with the government. 
