<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Myanmar to Jointly Fight Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Myanmar have
agreed to set up a joint task force to fight malaria and HIV cases
along the border of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The joint task force will be formed immediately by the health
ministries of the two governments to tackle the problem at the
operation level, according to the agreement reached on Monday
between Korn Dabbaransi, Thai deputy prime minister and minister
for public health, and Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt, first
secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and Development Council and
chairman of the Myanmar National Health Committee.
</P>
<P>
Korn Dabbaransi was on a one-day special mission to Myanmar to
present in person medical supplies and equipment worth over 1.8
million baht (over 49,000 U.S. dollars) to the country.
</P>
<P>
During their discussions the two leaders shared the feeling
that malaria and HIV cases had increased substantially in about
two to three years along the two countries' border from Chiangrai,
Tak, Maesot to Ranong.
</P>
<P>
Korn hoped the first meeting of the joint task force would be
held in Thailand's Chiangmai province in June or July this year.
</P>
<P>
The presentation of the Thai medical supplies and equipment to
Myanmar was done under the technical and economic cooperation
program of the two countries initiated in 1992 and these medical
supplies and equipment, which include those for combating malaria
and TB, will be used to enhance the quality of health care
services in Myanmar's rural and border areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
