<HEADLINE> IEA Forecasts Increasing Demand for Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The Executive Director of the
International Energy Agency (IEA) Robert Priddle said here Monday
that worldwide demand for energy will grow by 65 percent in the
following 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"Need for energy will grow dramatically in developing countries,
" Priddle told reporters in a press conference during the IEA
convention.
</P>
<P>
Priddle then forecast a huge increase in demand for natural gas
for its high burning efficiency and low pollution features. "In
the future, power plants burning natural gas will gradually
replace nuclear plants and those that use coal as the primary
energy source," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Priddle called on closer cooperation between governments in a
time when growing demand for energy is raising global concerns
over the heavy use of carbon dioxide-emitting fuels and poor
energy safety.
</P>
<P>
As to energy supply, while forecasting that the world will rely
more and more on petroleum production in the middle east, he said
that currently the European countries do not have reasons to worry
about power supplies, even without their own comprehensive
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Vice State Secretary of Ministry of Economy Honig
Peter said the demand for energy in his country will grow by 1
percent annually during the following five years, and that his
government will invest a total of 2 billion forints (7.69 million
U.S. dollars) in programs aimed at energy saving.
</P>
<P>
Found in 1974, the IEA is a major economic liaison organization
between governments for petroleum consuming countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
