<HEADLINE> Cuba, Caricom to Further Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Cuba and the 15-member
Caribbean Community (Caricom) are discussing how to tighten
economic and trade ties between them at a meeting that opened here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
An agreement to this effect is expected to be reached at the
two-day 6th Joint Cuba-Caricom session and the accord will be
ready for signing by the second half of this year, said Cuban
Foreign Trade Minister Ricardo Cabrisas and Caricom's Assistant
Secretary Byron Blake.
</P>
<P>
Blake viewed the agreement as a step forward in creating a
single Caribbean market and economy.
</P>
<P>
Cuba has seen increasing trade with the Caricom members since
the 1993 establishment of the joint session. Last year, Cuba's
trade with the Caricom bloc rose to 95 million U.S. dollars from
59 million dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Caricom was created in 1973 and seeks regional integration. It
has enlisted Antigua and Barbuda, Bahamas, Barbados, Belize,
Dominica, Grenada, Guyana, Haiti, Jamaica, Montserrat, Saint Kitts
and Nevis, Saint Lucia, Saint Vicent and the Grenadines, Suriname,
Trinidad and Tobago as members.  
</P>
