<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weather Forecast System Affected by Leap Year Glitch in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 29 (Xinhua) -- As a result of a computer glitch
stemming from an irregular leap year, erroneous data were found
early Tuesday at 43 of Japan's 500 regional meteorological
observation sites, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
Forty-three sites for the Automated Meteorological Data
Acquisition System in Japan's 23 prefectures had sent out
incorrect data, particularly in terms of precipitation and
temperatures, from around 1 a.m. local time Tuesday (1600GMT
Wednesday), the report quoted Meteorological Agency officials as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Gregorian calendar has a leap year every four years, in
which an extra day is added to account for the fact that the Earth
actually takes approximately 365.25 days to orbit the sun.
</P>
<P>
But over many centuries, the difference between this
approximate value and the more precise measurement of 365.242 days
accumulates significantly.
</P>
<P>
To offset this discrepancy, leap days are skipped in years
ending in "00," unless they are divisible by 400, making 2000 a
leap year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, computer programs that do not take into account
this special leap year could mistake February 29 for March 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Slash Tax: Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Canada will cut taxes by 58
billion Canadian dollars (about 40 billion U.S. dollars) in five
years, according to the country's budget for the year 2000
unveiled Monday by Finance Minister Paul Martin.
</P>
<P>
The budget also approves immediate new spending of up to 4.5
billion Canadian dollars (about 3.1 billion U.S. dollars), of
which 2.5 billion (about 1.7 billion U.S. dollars) will go for
health care and education, while 1.9 billion (about 1.3 billion U.
S. dollars) will go for national defense.
</P>
<P>
Under the five year tax-cut plan, personal income taxes will be
reduced by an average of 15 percent annually by the 2004-2005
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Middle-class Canadians will see a tax rate reduced from 26
percent to 23 percent, starting with a 2 percent drop to 24
percent in July, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Tax-free earnings will be raised to at least 8,000 Canadian
dollars (about 5,520 U.S. dollars), while middle and top income
tax rates kick in at higher levels of 35,000 Canadian dollars (
about 24,150 U.S. dollars) and 70,000 dollars (about 48,300 U.S.
dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
The tax reduction plan also includes the elimination of the 5
percent surtax on middle-class earners on July 1, 2000. The
surtax for high income earners will be phased out by 2004.
</P>
<P>
Child tax benefits will increase to a maximum of 2,400 dollars
(about 1,656 U.S. dollars), while maternity leave will be doubled
to one year as of December 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The corporate tax rates will be reduced to 21 percent from 28
percent for both big and small business sectors.
</P>
<P>
Canadians will focus on their future and this is indeed the
message of this budget, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Late last year, the minister projected a total of 95 billion
Canadian dollars (about 66 billion U.S. dollars) in budgetary
surplus for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
He has said that personal income tax cuts top the list of
things he wants to do with the surplus, which he expects to
achieve after a series of measures imposed in 1995 to tame the
deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
