<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Australian PM under New Pressure for  Aboriginal Reconciliation  By Qi Zijian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Australian newspaper reported Monday that Howard had
abandoned the deadline, which he committed to on the election
night 1998, to produce a blueprint for reconciliation between
Australia's blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with the Australian, Howard said the
process of reconciliation would take years and that the process
would be "incremental."
</P>
<P>
"We won't resolve it by May or December," Howard told the
Australian.
</P>
<P>
"The reconciliation process will take a long time and it will
unfold over a period of years," he said, adding "What really
matters are not so much documents ... these things are all
incremental."
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Howard's change of tack marked the
discarding of one of his commitments to making reconciliation a
second-term priority.
</P>
<P>
Aboriginal leaders have expressed concern and disappointment at
the decision.
</P>
<P>
Australian Democrats Senator Aden Ridgeway, the nation's only
Aboriginal federal MP, said Howard's decision could derail the
whole process of bringing black and white Australia together.
</P>
<P>
"I think this really has the potential to side rail the lot,"
Ridgeway told the ABC radio.
</P>
<P>
"Unless you have some sort of agreed outcome and some basic
conditions being met, people have nothing to aspire to and it sits
there as a concept out there in the ether," he said.
</P>
<P>
"No-one really understands and no-one commits themselves to it
and eventually it just dies," Ridgeway said.
</P>
<P>
Council for Aboriginal Reconciliation member Marjorie Thorpe
said she was concerned at the prime minister's stand after nine
years of work.
</P>
<P>
"I'm feeling a little bit alarmed I guess that the effort that
we've put into this process ... has been at a cost to all the
people involved," she told the ABC Radio.
</P>
<P>
"The commitment that there has been by many people over those
years needs to be recognized certainly by the prime minister and
the government," she said.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe said the council would continue its efforts as required
under the act and expressed confidence those efforts would not be
in vain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition Labor Party considered the federal
government had set back the reconciliation process.
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Kim Beazley said Howard was "absurdly chicken-
hearted" on the Aboriginal reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
He said it was tragic that the prime minister had abandoned his
end-of-year deadline for the reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
"He's destroying the joy and the moral weight in it. He's
destroying the opportunities," he told journalists after a shadow
cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Beazley said two simple and easy things were needed to start
the reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The first was to allow federal parliament to deliver the
apology on the stolen generation that most MPs favored.
</P>
<P>
The second was a statement acknowledging the original
Aboriginal custodianship of the land, he said.
</P>
<P>
Labor aboriginal affairs spokesman Daryl Melham said the
reconciliation was always going to be hard to achieve and Howard
had to accept much of the blame for the pace of change.
</P>
<P>
"The process has been stalled under his prime ministership for
four years, indeed I think it's fair to say it's gone backwards,"
he told ABC Radio.
</P>
<P>
But the country's peak indigenous body ATSIC described Howard's
move as an honest admission of failure and a point from which to
move on.
</P>
<P>
ATSIC Chairman Geoff Clark said Howard had admitted the
government's failure to properly recognize the true basis for the
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
He said most key players in the reconciliation process had also
acknowledged it would not be achieved by December 31.
</P>
<P>
"Now would be a good time for the prime minister to sit down
with indigenous leaders and discuss how we can address the
shocking socio-economic disadvantages suffered by our people and
also our quest for proper recognition of our rights," Clark said.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts also believed that Howard's decision was linked
to the growing opposition to saying sorry to the Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
Council for Aboriginal Reconciliation member Jackie Huggins
said she believed Howard's statement was linked to an unreleased
and incomplete council survey which found growing community
opposition to an apology to Aborigines for the past practices.
</P>
<P>
"I think that's fairly evident," she told ABC radio. "I think
the research has had a great bearing on how the prime minister has
spoken about the deadline," she added.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, federal Reconciliation Minister Philip
Ruddock said the government continued to act in areas like
indigenous health, education and housing, but believed
reconciliation was an ongoing process.
</P>
<P>
"Arbitrary deadlines are not going to produce changes in hearts
and minds," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Changes in hearts and minds will occur with goodwill and
people's willingness to keep working these issues through in a
very positive way," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
