<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyclone Hits Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The Northeastern areas of
Australia were hit heavily by Cyclone Steve and some residents are
now still isolated by rising waters.
</P>
<P>
The Cyclone slammed into the coastal areas on Sunday, bringing
160 kph winds and torrential rains leaving a trial of destruction
in its wake, Australian mess media reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Cairns, a coastal tourist city in Queensland, bore the brunt of
the category two Cyclone Steve. Street signs were twisted by the
wind and shop lay strewn across streets. Schools and many ships
and businesses were closed.
</P>
<P>
The Australian newspaper reported Tuesday that some suburbs of
the city were isolated by the flood and the local State Emergency
Services fielded more than 200 calls from residents seeking
tarpaulins for damaged roofs.
</P>
<P>
Only one casualty was reported so far. A 17-year-old boy riding
a tire tube down a north Queensland creek was found dead Tuesday
morning. He was hit Monday by a wall of water when played with a
group of friends.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Meteorology of Australia warned Monday night
against a new cyclone. The Bureau issued a cyclone watch for
coastal and island communities between Mornington Island in
Queensland and Alyangula on Groote Eylandt in the Northern
Territory.
</P>
<P>
A tropical low, following Steve, was based at Normanton at the
base of the Cape York Peninsula and moving Southwest, "There is
some possibility that (the low) will start to move towards the
Northwest, with the risk of a cyclone developing tomorrow night or
Wednesday in the southern Gulf of Carpentaria," the weather bureau
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
