from the Ulster Unionist Party and Sinn Fein which failed to
produce new proposals to resolve the impasse. (UK-N.Ireland-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish and Greek diplomats in the European Union (EU)
Working Group met here Monday to discuss Turkey's bid for EU
membership, a new development that showcased a political
rapprochement between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish delegation was led by deputy undersecretary of the
Foreign Ministry Uluc Ozulker while Greek Foreign Ministry
Secretary-General Stelios Perrakis headed the Greek delegation,
the Anatolia News Agency reported. (Turkey-Greece-EU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The Clinton administration said on Monday it
would not support the European Union's (EU) candidate to head the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and pledged to work with Europe
to find a strong European candidate who is able to command broad
support.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said
that Europe's candidate, German Deputy Finance Minister Caio Koch-
Weser, did not meet the criteria for a strong candidate of maximum
stature who would be able to command broad support from around the
world. (US-IMF-German)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian acting President Vladimir Putin on Monday
pledged to adopt state regulation on economy and to achieve much
political equality in the country if he is elected Russian
president in the March 26 elections.
</P>
<P>
State regulation is vital to national economy, and the state
will not be strong unless it regulates its economy, but state
regulation must not choke the market, Putin told a meeting of his
election campaign supporters in Moscow. (Russia-Putin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States conceded on Monday that there
was much work to be done before Syrian-Israeli peace talks could
resume.
</P>
<P>
"There's still an enormous amount of work to be done," State
Department spokesman James Rubin told a regular briefing. "We've
had a problem where each side wants its needs to be met first.
And that had made it not possible, as yet, to restart talks
formally." (US-Syria-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- Joerg Haider, known for his anti-foreigner statements
and praise of Nazi policies, resigned Monday as head of the far-
right Freedom Party, the Austria Press Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The move was seen as an attempt to reduce international
criticism of the new coalition government between Haider's
rightists and the center-right Austrian People's Party. (Austria-
Haider-Resign)
</P>
<P>
