<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kasparov Wins First Game at Linares Tournament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Top chess player Gary Kasparov
of Russia defeated Alexei Shirov of Spain with the white pieces in
the first game of the annual Linares Grandmaster Tournament on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Shirov, ranked fourth in the world, chose the venerable Petroff
Defense, which has a reputation as being solid and safe.
</P>
<P>
The players soon found themselves in a sharp tactical melee.
Kasparov later pushed his rooks to the seventh rank. Shirov
blundered with a move that cost him a knight and the game was over.
</P>
<P>
In other games, fellow Russian Vladimir Kramnik, ranked No. 3
in the world, won with black against Alexander Khalifman, the FIDE
World Champion. The No. 2 Wiswanathan Anand of India and Peter
Leko of Hungary, the world's top junior, played to a draw.
</P>
<P>
The Linares tournament is a double round-robin with the six
competitors playing each other twice, once with White and once
with Black. The players have two hours to make 40 moves and then
an hour and a half to make the next 20. A win garners one point
while a draw receives a half point.
</P>
<P>
The tournament, which features six of the world's best chess
players, ends March 10, with March 2 and 6 as rest days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
