<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Made Little Progress in Reducing Steel Output in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 29 (Xinhua) -- China has made little progress
in reducing its steel output in January this year due to the
reluctance of small and medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Because of a surplus of steel, the steel price has continued to
drop. Last year China decided to cut its output of steel, but with
little results.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will continue this year to make sure that the annual
steel output remains within 110 million tons, a 10 percent
decrease from 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics from the National Bureau of
Statistics, the steel industry produced some 10.04 million tons of
steel in January, 1.78 percent more than the projected quota.
</P>
<P>
The sector's 46 key giant enterprises, with annual output
exceeding 500,000 tons, cut their steel output significantly.
Total output dropped 4.18 percent from the same period last year.
Of these 46 enterprises, 27 met their reduction quota, including
China's five largest steel producers--Anshan Iron and Steel,
Baoshan Iron and Steel, Wuhan Iron and Steel and Capital Iron and
Steel.
</P>
<P>
However, the reluctance of small and medium-sized enterprises
to meet their reduction quotas has posed a serious threat to
restructuring China's steel industry.
</P>
<P>
Apart from these 46 enterprises, enterprises produced 1.49
million tons of steel in January, accounting for 15 percent of the
total and exceeding the quota by an astonishing 48.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Metallurgical Industry have taken
drastic measures to force reluctant enterprises to reduce their
steel output this month.
</P>
<P>
A special committee was formed to carry out the task of closing
down small steel factories nationwide and to manage steel output
on a monthly basis.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has also introduced policies to further
reduce the production of steel. Many favorable policies such as
lending loans for the restructuring enterprises and debt-to-equity
swaps will not be given to enterprises that can't meet the quota.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
