<HEADLINE> Leboeuf Plans to Quit in Two Years Time  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Frenchman Frank Leboeuf has
revealed he may quit the game at the top with Chelsea in two years
' time.
</P>
<P>
Leboeuf rejected a move to Tuesday night's Champions League
opponents Marseille just four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Although clubs must deal with each other first, Marseille
apparently contacted Leboeuf last month after hearing he was
unhappy at Stamford Bridge following the misconduct charge which
he faced for stamping on Leeds forward Harry Kewell.
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old defender's answer was an emphatic 'no' because
he is determined to see out the remaining two years of his
contract at Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
Winning the Champions League and the Premiership title remain
unfulfilled objectives in his career, even though he acknowledges
the increasingly frantic pace and physical nature of the English
game is taking its toll on players.
</P>
<P>
While his future remains unclear, he spelled out his desire
never to be "pitied at the age of 36, playing in the Second
Division" -even though he insisted Alan Shearer is quitting the
international scene too early at 29.
</P>
<P>
The French World Cup winner has flown back to his home city of
Marseille as Chelsea prepared to return to Champions League action
after a lengthy break to face the club with which Didier Deschamps
and Marcel Desailly both won the European Cup.
</P>
<P>
Leboeuf declared: "Before coming to Chelsea, I almost signed
for Marseille two weeks beforehand - but Strasbourg wouldn't let
me go.
</P>
<P>
"Then, four weeks ago, they called me to ask me to join them.
</P>
<P>
"It was the open transfer market in France. Many players had
left the club; they heard I had some problems at Chelsea and
because I was from Marseille they were interested in me. But I
told them I had a contract at Chelsea and I was happy here," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
