<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Experts Explore Solutions for Black Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Security experts on Tuesday
concluded a two-day discussion in Istanbul on dealing with the
black money issue, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The senior-level panel discussion, entitled "The Financial
Sources of Organized Crime," was held largely behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, experts who follow international black money
called for exploring new methods to track down and cut off the
financial sources of mafia and terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
Emin Arslan, head of the Organized Crime and Smuggling Bureau of
the Istanbul Police Department, noted in his speech that the
meeting focused on the financial sources of organized crime gangs
because the matter threatens the whole financial system.
</P>
<P>
"We have achieved important success in the struggle against
organized crime recently," Arslan claimed.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, organized by the Istanbul Police Department and
Marmara University's Law Faculty, was attended by Turkish police
officers and dozens of security experts from some European
countries.
</P>
<P>
Istanbul, Turkey's largest city with a population of 10 million,
lies across Asia and Europe, serving as a bridge geographically,
culturally and economically. Local and international organized
crime gangs have also found way into the unique city, committing
various kinds of political and terrorist crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
