<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Design Laser Defence for Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Canada wants to be the first to
design a laser defence for aircraft against incoming missiles, the
Ottawa Citizen reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Department of National Defence scientists are
attempting to equip a Hercules transport plane or a helicopter
with the laser system, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Laser would track the launch of an enemy ground-to-air
missile and "blind" the incoming rocket, making it lose sight of
its target.
</P>
<P>
The system would use what is called a laser dazzler to deal
with portable, shoulder-fired heat-seeking missiles, such as the
American-built Stinger.
</P>
<P>
A pilot project of 500,000 Canadian dollars (about 344,550 U.S.
dollars) has already been worked out for a laboratory prototype.
Scientists will run experiments using a stationary missile,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. defence company has built a laser dazzler, but the
Canadian device would be the first to combine both a dazzler and a
laser to detect missiles, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
