<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela, US Sign Joint Energy Declaration. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- A joint Energy Declaration was
signed Tuesday by Venezuelan Oil Minister Ali Rodriguez and U.S.
Secretary of Energy Bill Richardson, the Venezuelan Ministry
announced.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting held in London on Tuesday, the ministers
confirmed the importance of the economic and energy relations
between both countries and agreed to continue talks about the
world crude market and press the bilateral energy collaborations.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that oil supply at reasonable prices is
important and volatility of international prices will injure
consumer and producer countries.
</P>
<P>
In the same way, Rodriguez reiterated the Venezuelan
commitment to discuss with the other consumer and producer
countries about the crude market real situation, the economy and
the production levels, to protect growth and investments in the
area.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richardson had previous talked in Britain with his
counterparts from Mexico, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and Norway, asking
them to increase crude output to avoid price surge. He has voiced
concerns that high oil prices could cause a slowdown in the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
However, Rodriguez said on Monday that he did not expect the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to increase
output during the second quarter of this year because a seasonal
dip in demand during the period.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela is OPEC's second-largest producer and a leading
player in arranging the output cuts that rescued prices from their
lowest in a generation. Venezuela is also the largest oil supplier
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
A final OPEC decision is not expected until ministers meet in
Vienna on March 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says He May Still Use Strategic Oil Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Tuesday that he may use the Strategic Petroleum Reserve if
other options fail to reduce oil prices.
</P>
<P>
"I have not taken the petroleum reserve issue off the table,
and I certainly wouldn't do that in the event that we don't seem
to have any other options," Clinton said before leaving the White
House for a political trip to Florida.
</P>
<P>
Several Northeast lawmakers have urged the administration to
release oil from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, but Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson and other administration officials have
repeatedly said they do not intend to do that. The reserve is
designed to ease supply disruptions and not to influence prices.
</P>
<P>
There is also concern that if the strategic reserve were tapped
it would make it more difficult to convince members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to increase
production when they meet in March to consider future production
strategies.
</P>
<P>
If production goes up, "then oil prices will go down, the
gasoline prices will go down, and that's really what is needed
here," Clinton said. "We'll see. I'm encouraged that that might
occur."
</P>
<P>
Richardson visited several leading oil-producing countries this
weekend but failed to obtain any firm promises that OPEC would
agree to significantly raise its self-imposed production cuts.
</P>
<P>
The cuts have caused oil prices to soar, from 11.37 U.S.
dollars a barrel a year ago to a nine-year high of around 30
dollars a barrel, and led to the highest average U.S. gasoline
prices ever. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
