<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 29 (Xinhua) -- The blue chip stocks
continued its recovery from a big selloff last week while the
technology shares hitting the new record high on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At the close of session, the Dow Jones industrial average rose
89.66 at 10,128.31. The blue chips rebounded above 10,000 Monday
after falling below the five digital mark last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 118.84 at 4,696.69, surpassing the
record closing high of 4,617.65 points set last Thursday and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 18.37 at 1,366.42.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied as investors rushed in computer chips and
equipment stocks following the wide-ranging recommendations on
those sectors from investment banks Salomon Smith Barney and Chase
H&AMP;Q. Companies like Xilinx, LSI Logic, Motorola and Applied
Materials rose, leading the Nasdaq index higher.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's rise was particularly attributed to the Hewlett-
Packard's strong performance. The computer company rose sharply
after a Salomon analyst said its shares should reach 166 U.S.
dollars per share.
</P>
<P>
General Electric, AT&AMP;T and Home Depot also helped the index to
move higher. General Electric rose on the news that it will team
up with Boeing to build long-haul 777 jetliners while AT&AMP;T and
Home Depot surged as investors continued bargain-huanting after
last week's steep selloff.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 8.44 at 592.64 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 8.85 at 973.23. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 20.03 at 577.71.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,825 up, 1,192 down and 501
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increase to 1.18 billion shares from 1.02 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
