<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Supports Convening International Conference on Illicit Trade of Small Arms, Light Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- China supports the
convocation of an international conference on the illicit trade in
small arms and light weapons in all its aspects in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Shen Guofang, the deputy Chinese
permanent representative to the United Nations, took the floor at
the first session of the Preparatory Committee for the proposed
international conference.
</P>
<P>
China "will actively participate in its preparatory process,"
Shen said.
</P>
<P>
"China therefore sincerely hopes that this preparatory meeting
will be a success so as to lay a solid foundation for the smooth
convocation of the subsequent preparatory meetings and the
Conference in 2001," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The illicit trade in small arms and light weapons has in
recent years stood out as a hot issue, arousing the grave concern
of the international community," he said.
</P>
<P>
"China is firmly opposed to the illicit trade in any weapons,
including small arms and light weapons," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the scope and objective of the Conference, "we hold that
the Conference and its Preparatory Committee should conduct their
work in strict accordance with the mandate as set out by the
report of the Group of Governmental Experts on Small Arms as
endorsed by (relevant) General Assembly resolution," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee Monday began its first session here
for the U.N. Conference on illicit trade in small arms and light
weapons, which is slated for 2001.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee for the United Nations Conference on
the Illicit Trade in Small Arms and Light Weapons in All Its
Aspects held the session, which is scheduled to end on March 3, to
decide the dates and venue of the 2001 Conference as well as on
the dates and venues of its subsequent sessions.
</P>
<P>
During the first two days of the session, the Committee will
elect the member of its bureau and hold its general debate, after
which it will exchange views on the agenda items concerned.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the proliferation of small arms and light weapons
first appeared on the international political agenda in December
1995 when the General Assembly requested the U.N. Secretary-
General, with the assistance of a panel of experts, to report on
the nature and causes of their accumulation and transfer, and on
ways and means to prevent and reduce them.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997, a number of global and regional initiatives have
emerged to curb the destabilizing accumulation and transfer of
small arms. Those include a moratorium on the importation,
exportation and manufacturing of small arms and light weapons in
West Africa by the Economic Community of West African States (
ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
Negotiations are also under way in Vienna to elaborate an
international convention against transnational crime, including a
revised draft protocol against the illicit manufacturing of and
trafficking in firearms, ammunition and other relevant materials.
Those negotiations are expected to conclude later in the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0345 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy: Foreign Trade Surplus Almost Halved in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Italy's foreign trade surplus for
1999 fell by almost half to 25.352 trillion (about 12.7 billion U.
S. dollars) from 48.417 trillion lire (about 24.3 billion U.S.
dollars) in 1998, according to figures released Tuesday by the
Italian national statistics bureau Istat.
</P>
<P>
The Istat figures showed that trade with non-European Union
countries for the entire year showed a surplus of 24.266 trillion,
compared to 15.807 trillion in 1998, with imports up 7.3 percent
to 154.326 trillion and exports down 2.9 percent to 178.592
trillion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, trade with EU countries during 1999 showed a surplus
of 1.122 trillion lire, which was a drop of more than 7 trillion
lire over 1998.
</P>
<P>
Istat said that the biggest surpluses were posted in the
machine, manufacturing, clothing and leather industries, while
minerals, electrical appliances, vehicles and chemical products
were the areas with the largest deficits.
</P>
<P>
For the month of December alone, exports rose 10.8 percent over
the same month in 1998 and 0.9 percent over November 1999, while
imports jumped 23.7 percent compared to December 1998 and 4
percent compared to November.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said that trade in December with EU countries was
characterized by a 4.1 percent climb in exports compared to
December 1998 and a 15.4 percent rise in imports.
</P>
<P>
Turning to figures for January, it said that trade with non-EU
countries showed a deficit of 1.379 trillion lire due to a 30.5
percent leap in exports and a 40.2 percent rise in imports.
</P>
<P>
It said that, in particular, exports to Russia leapt a massive
152.6 percent, while exports to Turkey jumped 70.6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
