<HEADLINE> Sudan Rebels Reject Talks With Expelled NGOs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese rebels said Tuesday
they would not negotiate with the 11 aid agencies which were
deported from southern Sudan for rejecting a new operating
agreement, accord to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The organizations, including Medecines Sans Frontieres, World
Vision, Oxfam and Care International, were ordered out of regions
held by the Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) by Tuesday
noon.
</P>
<P>
The agencies object to conditions in the document which would
give rebels more control over the agencies' operations, and would
allow them to charge for activities such as aircraft landings and
movement within rebel- held territory.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA broke off negotiations with the agencies in
mid-January and gave them an ultimatum to leave.
</P>
<P>
All expatriate staff had been evacuated, either by road or air,
by early Tuesday, the aid agencies said.
</P>
<P>
The agencies estimate they assist around 1.6 million people in
hunger- stricken southern sudan, a region which has been ravaged
by a 17-year war between the islamic government and the mainly
christian and animist rebels.
</P>
<P>
"Our entire operation has been put on hold," said Nigel Marsh,
 spokesman for World Vision. "We need to ensure aid is given out
without partiality, according to need, not according to politics."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations agencies are exempt from the agreement and
will continue their operations as normal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
