<HEADLINE> Nigeria Vows to Attract $10 Billion Investment Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo said Monday that his government is determined to attract
at least 10 billion U.S. dollar investment annually.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of a three-day Commonwealth-Nigeria
Investment Conference in the capital Abuja, Obasanjo said that all
legal and administrative constraints to foreign investment had
been removed while the process of entry into and exit from the
country's economy by foreigners had been simplified.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said that his government would make all possible
efforts to drastically reduce the cost of doing business in the
country through the rehabilitation of infrastructure and
privatization exercise, stressing that "Nigerian conditions must
become internationally competitive."
</P>
<P>
The government was committed to reducing Nigeria's debt burden
through negotiations with the various creditors, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has been undertaking painstaking efforts to attract
foreign investors and demand western creditors to write off its
debt in order to revitalize its ailing economy after Obasanjo's
coming into power last May, ending 15-year military rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
