<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mysterious Disease Threatens Flamingos in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 29 (Xinhua) -- A mysterious disease is
killing tens of thousands of flamingos on Lake Bogoria in Rift
Valley Province, central Kenya, the East African Standard reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted conservationists as saying human pollution is
the cause of the disease which has since last July killed up to
50,000 birds on the lake.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the world's flamingo population live on the
eastern Rift Valley lakes, with vast majority living on the
30-square-kilometers Lake Bogoria, the real haven left for the
bird in the country.
</P>
<P>
"In every single bird which we collected and analyzed tissues,
we found up to nine or 10 heavy metals," said Gideon Motelin who
specializes in flamingo studies at Kenya's Egerton University.
</P>
<P>
"It is not normal to find arsenic, lead, mercury, chromium and
copper in the livers and kidneys of these birds," he said, adding
that traces of pesticide have also been found in the body tissue
of the dead birds.
</P>
<P>
Conservationists believe that the source of pollution is the
farms near Lake Nakuru, about 100 kilometers south of Bogoria.
Flamingos abandoned Lake Nakuru two years ago due to pollution as
the lake became virtually uninhabitable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000229.0361 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 </DATE_TIME>
