<HEADLINE> Uganda, Sudan to Resume Talks in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and the Sudan will
resume ministerial talks on the implementation of the peace
agreement signed by the two countries' presidents last December.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Minister for Presidency Ruhakana Rugunda told Xinhua on
Tuesday that the talks would start on Wednesday in the Kenyan
capital Nairobi and last through to the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"We would discuss what major progress we have achieved so far
in the implementation of the agreement and what should be done
next," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement, brokered by former U.S. President Jimmy
Carter, committed the two countries to ending hostility and
returning prisoners of war or people abducted by rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to restore full diplomatic relations by the end of
February if the commitment was fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
On several occasions, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
expressed his dissatisfaction with the lag of its implementation,
saying that the Sudanese government did not honor its promise of
returning all the children abducted by the rebel Lord's Resistance
Army in northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and the Sudan have been accusing each other of backing
rebel activities on their respective land and cut diplomatic
relations in April 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
