<HEADLINE> Angolan Rebels Lose 80 Percent Conventional Forces: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUANDA, February 29 (Xinhua) -- Angolan rebel leader Jonas
Savimbi has lost 80 percent of his conventional forces since last
October, a repentant rebel general was quoted here on Tuesday by
the official newspaper Jornal de Angola as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to General Diogenes Malaquias, the ex-chief of the
operation division of the rebel Headquarters of the General Staff,
Savimbi suffered a desertion of 80 percent of his effectives in
last October during the battles around the central city Andulo, a
traditional rebel military headquarter which was taken over by the
government troops on October 18, 1999.
</P>
<P>
 At this moment, the rebel troops are seriously shortstaffed,
with the conventional effectives accounting for less than 20
percent of its number in 1999, said General Malaquias, who did not
mention the loss of Savimbi's guerrilla forces.
</P>
<P>
According to the repentant general, most of the rebel soldiers
still loyal to Savimbi are guerrillas, who have been launching
road ambushes, guerrilla warfares and other destructive actions
against the government's targets. It was estimated last year by
the Angolan government that Jonas Savimbi had some 60,000
effectives, including 40,000-strong conventional troops and 20,000
guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
